{{Jesus}}
The '''Christ myth theory''' (also known as the '''Jesus myth theory''', '''Jesus mythicism''', or '''Jesus ahistoricity theory'''){{sfnp|Lataster|2015a|ps=none}} is "the view that the person known as [[Jesus Christ|Jesus of Nazareth]] had no historical existence."{{sfnp|Gullotta|2017|p=310}} Alternatively, in terms given by [[Bart D. Ehrman|Bart Ehrman]] as per his criticism of mythicism,{{sfnp|Lataster|2016|ps=none}} "the historical Jesus did not exist. Or if he did, he had virtually nothing to do with the [[Origins of Christianity|founding of Christianity]]."{{refn|group=q|name="Ehrman_def"}}

According to mythicists, the accounts of Jesus are mostly, or completely, of a mythical nature; and if there was a historical Jesus, close to nothing can be known about him. Most Christ mythicists follow a threefold argument: they question the reliability of the [[Pauline epistles]] and the [[Gospel]]s regarding the historicity of Jesus; they note the lack of information on Jesus in non-Christian sources from the first and early second century; and they argue that early Christianity was [[Religious syncretism|syncretistic]] and mythological from the beginning, as reflected in both the Pauline epistles and the gospels. Therefore, Christianity was not founded on the shared memories of a man, but rather a shared [[mytheme]].

The Christ myth theory is a [[fringe theory]], supported by few [[Academic tenure|tenured]] or [[emeritus]] specialists in [[biblical criticism]] or cognate disciplines.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2003|pp=658, 660}}{{sfnp|Burridge|Gould|2004|p=34}}<ref name="Ehrman Blog"/>{{refn|group=q|name="Gullotta.2017.fringe"}} It deviates from the [[Historical Jesus|mainstream historical view]], which is that while the gospels include many legendary elements, these are religious elaborations added to the accounts of a historical Jesus who was [[Crucifixion of Jesus|crucified]] in the 1st-century Roman province of [[Judea (Roman province)|Judea]].{{Sfnp|Ehrman|2012|ps=none}}{{Sfnp|Stanton|2002|pp=143ff}}
{{TOC limit|3}}

== Jesus and the origins of Christianity ==
{{See also|Jesus in Christianity|Historicity of Jesus|Sources for the historicity of Jesus|Historical Jesus|Quest for the historical Jesus|Portraits of the historical Jesus}}

The [[origins of Christianity|origins]] and rapid rise of Christianity, as well as the historical Jesus and the [[historicity of Jesus]], are a matter of longstanding debate in theological and historical research. While Christianity may have started with an early nucleus of followers of Jesus,{{refn|group=q|name="Dunn.2003.174"}} within a few years after the presumed death of Jesus in {{circa|AD 33}}, at the time [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] started preaching, a number of "Jesus-movements" seem to have been in existence, which propagated divergent interpretations of Jesus' teachings.{{sfnp|Mack|1995|ps=none}}{{sfnmp|1a1=King|1y=2008|1p=70|2a1=Behr|2y=2013|2pp=5–6}} A central question is how these communities developed and what their original convictions were,{{sfnp|Mack|1995|ps=none}}{{sfnp|King|2011|ps=none}} as a wide range of beliefs and ideas can be found in [[early Christianity]], including [[adoptionism]] and [[docetism]],{{refn|group=q|name="Ehrman.2015"}} and also [[gnosticism|Gnostic traditions]] which used Christian imagery,{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Pagels.1975.1979.Ehrman.2005"}} which were all deemed [[Heresy in Christianity|heretical]] by [[proto-orthodox Christianity]].{{sfnp|Ehrman|2003|ps=none}}{{refn|group=q|name="Green.2008.239"}}

Mainstream scholarship views Jesus as a real person who was subsequently [[Divinization (Christian)|deified]],{{sfnp|Ehrman|2012|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Stanton|2002|pp=143ff}} whereas traditional Christian theology and dogmas view Jesus as the incarnation of God/Christ on earth. Mythicists take yet another approach, presuming a widespread set of Jewish ideas on personified aspects of God, which were subsequently historicised when proto-Christianity spread among non-Jewish converts.

=== Mainstream historical view ===
{{See also|Textual criticism|Historical criticism|Biblical hermeneutics|Quest for the historical Jesus}}

Jesus is being studied by a number of scholarly disciplines,{{efn-lr|name=Biblical.studies}} using a variety of textual critical methods.{{efn-lr|[[Quest for the historical Jesus|Criteria being used]] to determine whether Biblical passages can be attributed to Jesus include [[criterion of multiple attestation|multiple attestation]], [[criterion of dissimilarity|dissimilarity]], [[criterion of embarrassment|embarrassment]], historical plausibility, rejection and execution, and congruence.}} These critical methods, and the [[quest for the historical Jesus]], have led to a [[demythologization]] of Jesus, and the mainstream historical view is that while the gospels include mythical or legendary elements, these are religious interpretations of the life and death of a historical Jesus who did live in 1st-century Roman Palestine.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2012|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Ehrman|2014|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Stanton|2002|pp=143ff}}{{efn-lr|name="Greater.Judea"}} While scholars differ on the historicity of specific episodes described in the Biblical accounts of Jesus,{{sfnp|Powell|2013|p=168}} the baptism and the crucifixion are two events in the life of Jesus which are subject to "almost universal assent".{{efn-lr|name="Jesus.Biography"}} According to historian [[Alanna Nobbs]],
{{quote|While historical and theological debates remain about the actions and significance of this figure, his fame as a teacher, and his crucifixion under the Roman prefect [[Pontius Pilate]], may be described as historically certain.<ref>[[Alanna Nobbs]] and Edwin Judge ap. {{cite web|last=Dickson|first=John|authorlink=John Dickson (author)|title=Best of 2012: The irreligious assault on the historicity of Jesus |url=http://www.abc.net.au/religion/articles/2012/12/24/3660194.htm |website=ABC Religion and Ethics|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=2 May 2018|language=en-AU|date=24 December 2012}}</ref>}}

New Testament scholar [[Bart D. Ehrman]] states that Jesus "certainly existed, as virtually every competent scholar of antiquity, Christian or non-Christian, agrees,"{{sfnp|Ehrman|1999|p=248}}{{sfnp|Ehrman|2011|p=285}} and also states that the existence of Jesus and his crucifixion by the Romans is attested to by a wide range of sources including [[Josephus]] and [[Tacitus]].{{sfnp|Ehrman|1999|p=248}}

While there is widespread scholarly agreement on the existence of Jesus as a historical figure, the [[Portraits of the historical Jesus|portraits of Jesus]] have often differed from each other and from the image portrayed in the gospel accounts.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2011|p=285}}{{sfnp|Theissen|Winter|2002|p=5}}{{sfnp|Cross|Livingstone|2005|ps=none}}{{efn-lr|According to Lataster, "the only thing New Testament scholars seem to agree on is Jesus' historical existence".<ref>{{cite news|last=Lataster|first=Raphael|title=Did historical Jesus really exist? The evidence just doesn't add up.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2014/12/18/did-historical-jesus-exist-the-traditional-evidence-doesnt-hold-up/|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=[[The Washington Post|WP Company LLC]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=December 18, 2014}}</ref>}}

===Traditional and modern Christian views===
{{See also|Christology|Christian apologetics|Christian fundamentalism|Biblical literalism|Evangelicalism}}

Traditional [[Christian theology]] and [[dogma]]s view Jesus as the incarnation of God/Christ on earth and as the [[Messiah]], whose death was a sacrifice that procured [[Atonement in Christianity|atonement]] for all who believe Jesus to be the [[Christ]]. According to Christian traditions, the Gospels and the Pauline epistles are inspired writings,{{sfnp|Stout|2011|ps=none}} which tell us in a reliable way about the birth and the life of Jesus, his ministry and sayings, and his [[Crucifixion of Jesus|crucifixion]] and resurrection, according to God's plan.{{efn-lr|name=Christian_fundamentalists}}

[[Liberal theology]], following the demythologization of Jesus, emphasises his earthly life as an exemplary model to be followed by Christians.{{efn-lr|name=Christian_Liberalism}}

=== Christ myth theorists ===
Most mythicists, like mainstream scholarship, note that Christianity developed within [[Hellenistic Judaism]], which was influenced by [[Hellenization#Hellenistic period|Hellenism]]. Early Christianity, and the accounts of Jesus are to be understood in this context. Departing from mainstream scholarship,  mythicists argue that the accounts of Jesus are mostly, or completely, of a mythical nature, questioning the mainstream [[paradigm]] of a historical Jesus in the beginning of the 1st century who was deified.

Carrier and other mythicists are critical of the conclusions and presuppositions of historicity proponents, questioning the value of consensus as a criterion for the historicity of Jesus.{{refn|group=q|name="conclusions_presuppositions"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Price.2009.61"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier.2012.21"}}

Some moderate authors, most notably Wells, have argued that there may have been a historical Jesus, but that this historical Jesus was fused with another Jesus-tradition, namely the mythological Christ of Paul.{{sfnp|Price|1999|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Thompson|Verenna|2012|ps=none}}{{refn|group=q|name="Robertson"}} Others, most notably the early Wells and [[Alvar Ellegård]], have argued that Paul's Jesus may have lived far earlier, in a dimly remembered remote past.{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Price.2009.2011.Doherty.2012"}}

The most radical mythicists hold, in terms given by Price, the "Jesus [[atheism]]" viewpoint, that is, there never was a historical Jesus, only a mythological character, and the [[mytheme]] of his incarnation, death, and exaltation. This character developed out of a [[Religious syncretism|syncretistic fusion]] of Jewish, Hellenistic and Middle Eastern religious thought; was put forward by Paul; and historicised in the Gospels, which are also syncretistic. Notable "atheists" are Paul-Louis Couchoud, Earl Doherty, Thomas L. Brodie, and Richard Carrier.{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier 2014 p614–616"}}

Some other authors argue for the Jesus [[agnosticism]] viewpoint. That is, we cannot conclude if there was a historical Jesus. And if there was a historical Jesus, close to nothing can be known about him. Notable "agnosticists" are Robert Price, Thomas L. Thompson, and Raphael Lataster.{{sfnp|Lataster|2014|loc=§.&nbsp;[https://openjournals.library.sydney.edu.au/index.php/LA/article/view/8328/8466 Raphael Lataster’s Jesus Agnosticism]}}{{refn|group=q|name="mix.agnosticism.atheism"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy.Boyd.2007.137"}}

While proponents like [[Earl Doherty]], Price, and Carrier, are concerned with the origins of Christianity and the genesis of the Christ-figure, the perception of and debate about the Christ myth theory has increasingly turned to the simpler question whether Jesus existed or not{{refn|group=q|name="existence.simplification"}} and consequently with some scholars proposing a more moderate position.{{refn|group=q|name="Davies.2012.evidence"}}

== Arguments ==
According to New Testament scholar [[Robert E. Van Voorst|Robert Van Voorst]], most Christ mythicists follow a threefold argument: they question the reliability of the Pauline epistles and the Gospels regarding the historicity of Jesus;{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2000.9.new-testament"}} they note the lack of information on Jesus in non-Christian sources from the first and early second century;{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2000.9.documentation"}} and they argue that early Christianity was syncretistic and mythological from the beginning.{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2000.9.syncretism"}}

===Overview of main arguments===
Most Christ mythicists argue that the evidence for the existence of a historical Jesus Christ is weak at best,{{refn|group=q|name="Evans.2008.25"}} pointing at a series of perceived peculiarities in the sources which they regard as untrustworthy for a historical account.{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Price.2011.36.Doherty.1999.1997"}} Early Christian and other sources lack biographical information on Jesus,{{refn|group=q|name="Bethune.2016"}} the so-called argument from silence.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}}{{refn|group=q|name="argument.from.silence"}} Instead, the Christ of [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]]{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}}{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Lataster.2015.Price.2009"}}{{efn-lr|name="Paul.Christology"}} and the Jesus of the Gospels are of a [[Mythology|mythical]] and [[Allegory|allegorical]] nature.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}}{{refn|group=q|name="Price.2006.66"}}{{efn-lr|name="Positive.argument"}} They further argue that the Gospels are a composite of various strands of thought,{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Price|2000|p=86}} relying on Jewish writings,{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Price.2011.36.Doherty.1999.1997"}} and note the similarities of early Christianity and the Christ figure with the [[mystery religions]] of the [[Greco-Roman world]].{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy.Boyd.2007.34"}}
* <!-- PAUL --> '''Paul's Jesus is a celestial being, not a historical person, or may have lived in a dim past''' – the [[Pauline epistles]] are older than the gospels but, aside from a few passages which may have been [[Christian interpolation|interpolations]], make no reference to a historical Jesus who lived in the flesh on Earth,{{refn|group=q|name="Lataster.2016.191"}} nor do they cite any sayings from Jesus. There is a complete absence of any detailed biographical information such as might be expected if Jesus had been a contemporary of Paul;{{refn|group=q|name="Wells.1982.22"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy2007_p202"}} instead, Paul refers to Jesus as an exalted being. Therefore, Paul is probably writing about either a mythical [[entity]],{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Wells.1999.1999.2009"}} a celestial deity,{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier.2014.53"}} "a savior figure patterned after similar figures within ancient mystery religions"{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy2007_p202"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Price2003_p350"}} named Jesus;{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Couchoud.1939.33.Price.2009.64"}}{{Refn|name="Price.2003.Name"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier.Zechariah.6"}} or a historical person who may have lived in a dim past, long before the beginnings of the [[Common Era]].
* <!-- GOSPELS --> '''The Gospels are not historical records''' – although the Gospels seem to present an historical framework, they are not historical records, but [[Theology|theological]] writings,{{refn|group=q|name="Van.Voorst.2000.13"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Thompson.2009.p3"}} which are based on a variety of sources and influences, including [[Old Testament]] writings,{{Refn|name="Price.scripture"}}{{sfnp|Thompson|2012}} Greek Stoic philosophy and the [[Exegesis|exegetical]] methods of [[Philo]].{{refn|group=q|name="Lataster.2014.19"}}{{efn-lr|name="Philo.exegesis"}} The [[genre]] of the Gospels are myth or legendary fiction{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy_Boyd2007_p314-315"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy_Boyd2007_p137-138"}}{{efn-lr|name="Mythotype"}} which have imposed "a fictitious historical narrative" on a "mythical cosmic savior figure"{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy_Boyd_2007"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2000.9.syncretism"}} by weaving together various pseudo-historical Jesus traditions,{{refn|group=q|name="Wells2013_p16"}}{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}}{{efn-lr|name="Jesus.traditions"}} most notably the "[[supernatural]] personage" of Paul's epistles{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}} and "ideas very important in the Jewish [[Wisdom literature]]".{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}}{{refn|group=q|name="Wells2013_p16"}}
* <!-- NO INDEPENDENT EYEWITNESS --> '''No independent eyewitness accounts''' – No independent eyewitness accounts survive, in spite of the fact that many authors were writing at that time.{{refn|group=q|name="Van.Voorst.2000.69"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy.Boyd.2007.163"}} Early second-century Roman accounts contain very little evidence{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2000.9.documentation"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy.Boyd.2007.32"}} and may depend on Christian sources.{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst2000_p13"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Lataster2015_p68"}}
* <!-- DIVERSITY AND PARALLELS --> '''Diversity in early Christianity, and parallels with other religions''' – Early Christianity was widely diverse and [[religious syncretism|syncretistic]], sharing common philosophical and religious ideas with other religions of the time.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}} Its origins cannot be traced to a single founding group, but must have been rooted in a wider religious movement. It arose in the Greco-Roman world of the first and second century AD, synthesizing [[Ancient Greek philosophy|Greek]] and [[Jewish philosophy#Ancient Jewish philosophy|Jewish philosophy]] of the [[Second Temple period]].{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2000.9.syncretism"}}{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} Parallels with other religions include the ideas of personified aspects of God,{{efn-lr|name="Personification"}} proto-Gnostic ideas, and [[salvation]] figures featured in [[Greco-Roman mysteries|mystery religions]], which were often (but not always) a [[dying-and-rising god]].{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Bromiley.1982"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Price.2000.86.88.91"}}{{efn-lr|name="Dying.god"}}

=== The Pauline epistles ===
[[File:Uncial 0220 Rom-4.23-5.3.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|A 3rd century fragment of Paul's [[letter to the Romans]]]]
{{Main|Pauline epistles|Authorship of the Pauline epistles}}

====Dating====

=====Mainstream view=====
The seven undisputed Pauline epistles considered by scholarly consensus to be [[Authorship of the Pauline epistles|genuine epistles]] are generally dated to AD 50–60 (i.e. approximately twenty to thirty years after the generally accepted time period for the death of Jesus around AD 30–36) and are the earliest surviving Christian texts that may include information about Jesus.{{sfnp|Tuckett|2001|ps=none}}{{refn|group=q|name="Johnson.2010.241"}}{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Miller.2017.1.Carrier.2016"}}

=====Mythicist views=====
Some mythicists have questioned the early dating of the epistles, raising the possibility that they represent a later, more developed strand of early Christian thought.

Theologian [[Willem Christiaan van Manen]] of the Dutch school of [[radical criticism]] noted various anachronisms in the Pauline Epistles. Van Manen claimed that they could not have been written in their final form earlier than the 2nd century. He also noted that the [[Marcionism|Marcionite school]] was the first to publish the epistles, and that [[Marcion]] ({{circa|85}} – {{circa|160}}) used them as justification for his gnostic and docetic views that Jesus' incarnation was not in a physical body. Van Manen also studied Marcion's version of [[Epistle to the Galatians|Galatians]] in contrast to the canonical version, and argued that the canonical version was a later revision which de-emphasized the Gnostic aspects.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Detering|first1=Hermann|title=The Dutch Radical Approach to the Pauline Epistles|journal=Journal of Higher Criticism|date=1996|volume=3|issue=2|pages=163–193|url=https://depts.drew.edu/jhc/detering.html|accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref>

Price wrote that "the historical Jesus problem replicates itself in the case of Paul," and that the epistles have the same limitations as the Gospels as historical evidence. Price sees the epistles as a compilation of fragments (possibly with a Gnostic core),<ref>{{cite book|last1=Price|first1=Richard M.|title=The Amazing Colossal Apostle |date=2012 |publisher=Signature Books |location=Salt Lake City |isbn=978-1-56085-216-2|page=viii}}</ref> and contends that Marcion was responsible for much of the Pauline corpus or even wrote the letters himself, while criticizing the [[Circumstantial ad hominem|circumstantial ''ad hominem'' fallacy]] of fellow Christ myth theorists holding the mid-first-century dating of the epistles (e.g. Galatians is conventionally dated {{circa|AD 53}}){{efn-lr|name=Ludemann}} for their own apologetical reasons.<ref>{{cite book |last=Price|first=Robert M.|authorlink=Robert M. Price |editor1=Thomas L. Thompson |editor2=Thomas S. Verenna |title="Is this Not the Carpenter?": The Question of the Historicity of the Figure of Jesus |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r4SQZwEACAAJ |year=2012 |publisher=Equinox |isbn=978-1-84553-986-3 |pages=95ff |chapter=Does the Christ Myth Theory Require an Early Date for the Pauline Epistles?}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Price |first=Robert M. |authorlink=Robert M. Price |title=The Christ-Myth Theory and Its Problems |year=2011 |publisher=American Atheist Press |isbn=978-1-57884-017-5 |pages=353ff |chapter=Does the Christ Myth Theory Require an Early Date for the Pauline Epistles?}}</ref> Price argues that passages such as [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Galatians#1:18–20|Galatians 1:18–20]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Galatians#4:4|Galatians 4:4]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Corinthians#15:3–11|1 Corinthians 15:3–11]] are late Catholic interpolations and that [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Thessalonians#2:14|1 Thessalonians 2:14–16]] was unlikely to have been written by a Jewish person.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Price |first1=Richard M. |title=The Amazing Colossal Apostle |date=2012 |publisher=Signature Books |location=Salt Lake City |isbn=978-1-56085-216-2 |pages=360–361, 415, 426, 491}}</ref>

====Lack of biographical information====

=====Mainstream view=====
Modern biblical scholarship notes that "Paul has relatively little to say on the biographical information of Jesus," viewing Jesus as "a recent contemporary."{{sfnp|Eddy|Boyd|2007|p=202}}{{sfnp|Stout|2011|p=64}} Bishop and historian [[Paul Barnett (bishop)|Paul Barnett]] explains that
{{quote|Paul's relative lack of detailed reference to the historical Christ is usually explained in one of two ways: either Paul knew only that there was such a man but knew (or cared to know) little more (Bultmann), or he knew quite a lot but didn't need to elaborate this in his letters beyond what his readers already knew.<ref name="Martin Hengel">{{cite book|last=Hengel|first=Martin|title=The four Gospels and the one Gospel of Jesus Christ: an investigation of the collection and origin of the Canonical Gospels|isbn=978-1-5633-8300-7}}</ref><ref name="Barnett.2009.184">{{cite book|last=Barnett|first=Paul|authorlink=Paul Barnett (bishop)|title=Finding the Historical Christ|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KPMIYtpKtDwC|year=2009|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-4890-1|page=184|chapter=Christ in Pauls Letters}}</ref>}}

=====Mythicist views=====
Wells criticized the infrequency of the reference to Jesus in the Pauline letters and has said there is no information in them about Jesus' parents, place of birth, teachings, trial nor crucifixion.<ref name=WellsT49/> Robert Price says that Paul does not refer to Jesus' earthly life, also not when that life might have provided convenient examples and justifications for Paul's teachings. Instead, revelation seems to have been a prominent source for Paul's knowledge about Jesus.{{sfnp|Price|2003}}

Wells says that the Pauline epistles do not make reference to [[Oral gospel traditions|Jesus' sayings]], or only in a vague and general sense. According to Wells, as referred to by Price in his own words, the writers of the New Testament "must surely have cited them when the same subjects came up in the situations they addressed."{{sfnp|Price|2011}}

=====Brother of the Lord=====
[http://biblehub.com/interlinear/1_corinthians/9-5.htm 1 Corinthians 9:5] and [http://biblehub.com/interlinear/galatians/1-19.htm Galatians 1:19] make reference to "the brothers of the Lord" and "James, the brother of the Lord" respectively. Per Galatians 1:19, mainstream scholarship holds that it attests that Paul met with [[James, brother of Jesus]].{{refn|group=q|name="Gullotta.2017.336"}}

Mythicists argue that 1 Corinthians 9:5 and Galatians 1:19 are references to a [[Fraternity|fraternal]] brotherhood, or that "Brother of the Lord" connotes a meaning other than a male sibling of Jesus.<ref group=q name="mix.Price.2009.2011" />

=====Jesus’ birth=====
[https://www.blueletterbible.org/kjv/gal/4/1/t_concf_1095004   Galatians 4:4] and  [https://www.blueletterbible.org/kjv/rom/1/1/t_concf_1047003 Romans 1:3] make reference to Jesus’ birth, being: "born ({{lang-grc|γενόμενον|genómenon|made}}) of [a] woman" and "born ({{lang-grc|γενομένου|genoménou|was made }}) of [the] seed of David" respectively. Mainstream scholarship holds that Galatians 4:4 attests that Paul knew Jesus was born of a human mother and that per Romans 1:3, Paul says that Jesus was born a descendant of David—a historical ancestor in Paul's view.{{refn|group=q|name="Gullotta.2017.330"}}{{sfnp|Tuckett|2001|ps=none}}<ref name=JRDunn143>''Jesus Remembered: Christianity in the Making'' by James D. G. Dunn (2003) {{ISBN|0802839312}} p. 143</ref><ref name=McK38/><ref name=Furnish19>''Jesus according to Paul'' by Victor Paul Furnish 1994 {{ISBN|0521458242}} pp. 19–20</ref><ref name=Barn95>''Jesus & the Rise of Early Christianity: A History of New Testament Times'' by Paul Barnett 2002 {{ISBN|0830826998}} pp. 95–96</ref>

Doherty and Carrier hold that Paul's unique usage of the term "made" in the context of these references is consistent with a "Celestial Jesus" who was born/incarnated when a human body was made for him.{{sfnp|Carrier|2014|p=570}} Wells contends that Paul's reference to Davidic descent "is surely to state an article of faith" and not an assertion of historical fact.{{sfnp|Wells|1982|p=175}}

=====Eucharist=====
[http://biblehub.com/interlinear/1_corinthians/11-23.htm 1 Corinthians 11:23–26] make reference to "the night" Jesus handled bread and wine, teaching Christians the theological ritual of the Lord's supper. Mainstream scholarship holds that it recalls the earthly life of Jesus "in the context of cultic rites that assumed his divinity."<ref group=q name="Young.2006.14" />

Mythicists argue that Paul's vision of Jesus inaugurating the Eucharist ritual is an [[Etiology|etiological]] myth.{{sfnp|Carrier|2014|pp=557ff}}

====Celestial being====

=====Mainstream view=====
Most scholars view the Pauline letters as essential elements in the study of the historical Jesus,{{sfnp|Tuckett|2001|ps=none}}<ref name=JRDunn143/><ref name=McK38>''Jesus Christ in History and Scripture'' by Edgar V. McKnight 1999 {{ISBN|0865546770}} p. 38</ref><ref name=Furnish43>Victor Furnish in ''Paul and Jesus'' edited by Alexander J. M. Wedderburn 2004 (Academic Paperback) {{ISBN|0567083969}} pp. 43–44</ref> and the development of early Christianity.{{sfnp|Mack|1995|ps=none}} New Testament scholar [[James Dunn (theologian)|James Dunn]] states that in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Corinthians#15:3|1 Corinthians 15:3]] Paul "recites the foundational belief," namely "that Christ died." According to Dunn, "Paul was told about a Jesus who had died two years earlier or so."<ref>''Jesus Remembered: Christianity in the Making'', Volume 1 by James D. G. Dunn (2003) {{ISBN|0802839312}} pp. 142–143.</ref> [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Corinthians#15:11|1 Corinthians 15:11]] also refers to others before Paul who preached the creed.<ref name=RMartin57/>

The Pauline letters incorporate creeds, or confessions of faith, that predate Paul, and give essential information on the faith of the early Jerusalem community around James, 'the brother of Jesus'.<ref name=Kruse41 >''Paul's Letter to the Romans'' by Colin G. Kruse (2012) {{ISBN|0802837433}} pp. 41–42.</ref><ref name=BAune>''The Blackwell Companion to The New Testament'' edited by David E. Aune 2010 {{ISBN|1405108258}} p. 424.</ref><ref name=RMartin57 >''Worship in the Early Church'' by Ralph P. Martin 1975 {{ISBN|0802816134}} pp. 57–58</ref>{{sfnp|Mack|1995|ps=none}} The Pauline epistles contain elements of a Christ myth and its cultus, such as the Christ hymn of [[Philippians 2]]:6–11, which portray Jesus as an incarnated and subsequently exalted heavenly being.{{Refn|name="Price.2003.Name"}}{{efn-lr|name=Ph2:6-11}}{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Mack.1988.98.Price.2000.75"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Price.2000.88.92.94"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy.Boyd.2007.93.136"}} These pre-Pauline creeds date to within a few years of Jesus' death and developed within the Christian community in Jerusalem.<ref name=Leith12 >''Creeds of the Churches, Third Edition'' by John H. Leith (1982) {{ISBN|0804205264}} p. 12.</ref> Scholars view these as indications that the incarnation and exaltation of Jesus was part of Christian tradition a few years after his death and over a decade before the writing of the Pauline epistles.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2014|ps=none}}<ref name="Bouma.2014"/>

Yet, the development of the early Christian views on Jesus' divinity is a matter of debate within contemporary scholarship. According to a longstanding consensus, the oldest Christology was an "exaltation Christology," according to which Jesus was subsequently "raised to divine status."<ref name=BE_2013.02.14>{{cite web|last1=Ehrman|first1=Bart D.|authorlink1=Bart D. Ehrman|title=Incarnation Christology, Angels, and Paul |url=https://ehrmanblog.org/incarnation-christology-angels-and-paul-for-members/|website=The Bart Ehrman Blog|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=February 14, 2013}}</ref> This "exaltation Christology" may have developed over time,{{sfnp|Mack|1995|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Ehrman|2003|ps=none}}<ref name="autogenerated1">Bart Ehrman, ''How Jesus became God'', Course Guide</ref> as witnessed in the Gospels,{{sfnp|Ehrman|2014|ps=none}} with the earliest Christians believing that Jesus became divine when he was resurrected.<ref name="autogenerated1"/><ref>Geza Vermez (2008), ''The Resurrection'', p.138-139</ref> Later beliefs shifted the exaltation to his baptism, birth, and subsequently to the idea of his eternal existence, as witnessed in the Gospel of John.<ref name="autogenerated1"/>  This "High Christology" is "the view that Jesus was a pre-existent divine being who became a human, did the Father’s will on earth, and then was taken back up into heaven whence he had originally come."<ref name=BE_2013.02.14/>{{sfnp|Ehrman|2014|ps=none}} Yet, as Ehrman notes, this subsequent "incarnation Christology" was also preached by Paul, and even predates him.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2014|ps=none}} According to the "Early High Christology Club," this "incarnation Christology" or "high Christology" did not evolve over a longer time, but was a "big bang" which arose in the first few decades of the church, as witnessed in the writings of Paul.<ref name="Bouma.2014">{{cite web|last=Bouma|first=Jeremy|title=The Early High Christology Club and Bart Ehrman — An Excerpt from "How God Became Jesus"|url=https://zondervanacademic.com/blog/how-god-became-jesus-bart-ehrman-high-christology-excerpt/|website=Zondervan Academic Blog|publisher=[[HarperCollins]] Christian Publishing|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=March 27, 2014}}</ref>{{sfnp|Ehrman|2014|ps=none}}{{efn-lr|The "Early High Christology Club" includes Martin Hengel, Larry Hurtado,{{refn|group=q|name="Hurtado.2005.p101"}} and Richard Bauckham.<ref name="Bouma.2014"/>{{refn|group=q|name="Loke.2017.5"}}}}

Scholars have also argued that Paul was a "mythmaker,"{{sfnp|Maccoby|1986}} who gave his own [[Council of Jerusalem|divergent interpretation]] of the meaning of Jesus,{{sfnp|Mack|1995|ps=none}} building a bridge between the Jewish and Hellenistic world,{{sfnp|Mack|1995|ps=none}} thereby creating the faith that became Christianity.{{sfnp|Maccoby|1986}}

=====Mythicist views=====
Christ myth theorists generally reject the idea that Paul's epistles refer to a real person.<ref name=Price62/><ref name=WellsT49/>

According to Doherty, the Jesus of Paul was a divine Son of God, existing in a spiritual realm{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}} where he was crucified and resurrected.{{sfnp|Doherty|2009}} This mythological Jesus was based on exegesis of the Old Testament and [[Vision (spirituality)|mystical visions]] of a risen Jesus.{{sfnp|Doherty|2009}}{{refn|group=q|name="vridar_Couchoud"}}

Carrier argues that Paul is actually writing about a celestial deity named Jesus: Carrier notes that there is little if any concrete information about Christ's earthly life in the Pauline epistles, even though Jesus is mentioned over three hundred times.<ref name="Carrier2014_location34725">{{cite book|last1=Carrier|first1=Richard|title=On the Historicity of Jesus|date=2014|publisher=Sheffield Phoenix Press|isbn=978-1-909697-70-6|page=location 34725|edition=Kindle}}</ref> According to Carrier, the genuine Pauline epistles show that the [[Saint Peter|Apostle Peter]] and the Apostle Paul believed in a visionary or dream Jesus, based on a [[pesher]] of [[Septuagint]] verses [[Book of Zechariah|Zechariah]] 6 and 3, [[Book of Daniel|Daniel]] 9 and [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 52–53.{{sfnp|Carrier|2014|loc=Chapter 4 and Chapter 11}} Carrier further argues that according to Paul (Philippians 2.7), Christ "came 'in the likeness of men' (homoiomati anthropon) and was found 'in a form like a man' (schemati euretheis hos anthropos) and (in Rom. 8.3) that he was only sent 'in the likeness of sinful flesh' (en homoiomati sarkos hamartias). This is a doctrine of a preexistent being assuming a human body, but not being fully transformed into a man, just looking like one".{{sfnp|Carrier|2014|p=570}}</ref>

The non-Pauline [[Epistle to the Hebrews]] is also relevant per [http://biblehub.com/interlinear/hebrews/5-7.htm Hebrews 5:7], "in the days of his flesh" Jesus cried and prayed to God to save him. Mythicists generally contend that this verse is anomalous with supposed traditions underlying the synoptic gospels, however Doherty and Carrier additionally hold that the phrase "in the days of his flesh" is consistent with a celestial Jesus.<ref group=q name="Wells.1982.60" />{{sfnp|Carrier|2014|p=570}}

====Jesus lived in a dim past====

=====Mythicist views=====
The early Wells, and [[Alvar Ellegård]], have argued that Paul's Jesus may have lived far earlier, in a dimly remembered remote past.{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Price.2009.2011.Doherty.2012"}}

Wells argues that Paul and the other epistle writers—the earliest Christian writers—do not provide any support for the idea that Jesus lived early in the 1st century and that—for Paul—Jesus may have existed many decades, if not centuries, before.<ref name=WellsT49>''Can We Trust the New Testament?'' by George Albert Wells 2003 {{ISBN|0812695674}} pp. 49–50</ref><ref>Martin, Michael. ''The Case Against Christianity''. Temple University Press, 1993, p. 38.</ref> According to Wells, the earliest strata of the New Testament literature presented Jesus as "a basically supernatural personage only obscurely on Earth as a man at some unspecified period in the past".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wells|first=GA|date=September 1999|title=Earliest Christianity|journal=New Humanist|volume=114|issue=3|pages=13–18|url=http://www.infidels.org/library/modern/g_a_wells/earliest.html|accessdate=January 11, 2007}}</ref> In ''The Jesus Myth'', Wells argues that two Jesus narratives fused into one: Paul's mythical Jesus and a minimally historical Jesus whose teachings were preserved in the [[Q document]], a hypothetical common source for the [[Gospel of Matthew|Gospels of Matthew]] [[Gospel of Luke|and Luke]].{{sfnp|Wells|1999}}

Some myth proponents assert that the writings of [[Epiphanius of Salamis]] makes reference to a group of [[Jewish Christian]]s who held that Jesus lived during the reign of [[Alexander Jannaeus]]—"placing Jesus about 100 BCE"—and that this was also the view presented in the Jewish writings about [[Jesus in the Talmud]] and the [[Toledot Yeshu]].{{refn|group=q|name="Price.2006.240"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Mead"}}

According to the ''Panarion'' by Epiphanius, the Jewish-Christian sect known as the [[Nazarene (sect)|Nazarenes]] (Ναζωραιοι) began as Jewish converts of the [[Apostles]].{{refn|group=q|name="Panarion"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier.2009.p293"}} Richard Carrier contends that "Epiphanius, in ''Panarion'' 29, says there was a sect of still-Torah-observant Christians who taught that Jesus lived and died in the time of Jannaeus, and all the Jewish sources on Christianity that we have (from the [[Talmud]] to the Toledot Yeshu) report no other view than that Jesus lived during the time of Jannaeus".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carrier |first1=Richard |authorlink1=Richard Carrier|title=Ehrman on Jesus: A Failure of Facts and Logic|url=http://www.richardcarrier.info/archives/1026|website=Richard Carrier Blog|accessdate=August 27, 2017|date=April 19, 2012}}</ref>{{sfnp|Carrier|2014|pp=284ff}}

=====Mainstream criticism=====
Theologian [[Gregory A. Boyd]] and Paul Rhodes Eddy, Professor of Biblical and Theological Studies at [[Bethel University (Minnesota)|Bethel University]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bethel.edu/academics/faculty/eddy-paul |title=Paul Eddy |publisher=Bethel University |accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref> criticise the idea that "Paul viewed Jesus as a cosmic savior who lived in the past," referring to various passages in the Pauline epistles which seem to contradict this idea. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Galatians#1:19|Galatians 1:19]], Paul says he met with [[James, brother of Jesus|James]], the "Lord's brother";{{refn|group=q|name="Gullotta.2017.336"}} [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Corinthians#15:3|1 Corinthians 15:3–8]] refers to people to whom Jesus' had appeared, and who were Paul's contemporaries; and in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Thessalonians#2:14|1 Thessalonians 2:14–16]] Paul refers to the Jews "who both killed the Lord Jesus" and "drove out us" as the same people, indicating that the death of Jesus was within the same time frame as the persecution of Paul.{{sfnp|Boyd|Eddy|2007|p=46–47}} Boyd and Eddy doubt that Paul viewed Jesus similar to the savior deities found in ancient mystery religions.{{sfnp|Boyd|Eddy|2007|p=45–47}}

===The Gospels are not historical records===
{{Main|The Gospels}}

==== Dating and authorship ====
The general consensus of modern scholars is that Mark was the first gospel to be written and dates from no earlier than {{circa|AD 65}}, while Matthew and Luke, which use it as a source, were written between AD 80 and 85.{{sfnp|Reddish|2011|pp=73–74, 144}} The composition history of John is complex, but most scholars see it taking place in stages beginning as early as before AD 70 and extending as late as the end of the century.{{sfnp|Reddish|2011|pp=73–74, 144}} None of the authors were eyewitnesses to the life of Jesus,{{sfnp|Baggett|2008|p=7}} "(t)he common wisdom in the academy is that stories and sayings of Jesus circulated for decades, undergoing countless retellings and embellishments before being finally set down in writing."{{sfnp|Review of Bauckham|2006|p=225}} According to scholar in theology [[Richard Bauckham]] the authors may have received their information very close to eyewitness reports.{{sfnp|Bauckham|2017}}{{refn|group=q|name="Review.Bauckham.2006.eyewitness"}}

According to Carrier, "The Gospels cannot really be dated, nor are the real authors known. Their names were assigned early, but not early enough for us to be confident they were accurately known. It is based on speculation that Mark was the first, written between AD 60 and 70, Matthew second, between AD 70 and 80, Luke (and Acts) third, between AD 80 and 90, and John last, between AD 90 and 100".<ref>{{cite web |first1=Richard |last1=Carrier |authorlink1=Richard Carrier|title=The Formation of the New Testament Canon |url=https://www.academia.edu/276996/The_Formation_of_the_New_Testament_Canon|website=Academia |accessdate=September 24, 2016}}</ref>

==== Genre ====
According to [[Richard Burridge (priest)|Richard Burridge]], priest and biblical scholar, any study of the Gospels must first determine the genre under which they fall, in order to interpret them correctly, since genre "is a key convention guiding both the composition and the interpretation of writings".<ref>Burridge, R. A. (2006). Gospels. In J. W. Rogerson & Judith M. Lieu (Eds) ''The Oxford Handbook of Biblical Studies''. Oxford: Oxford University Press. p. 433</ref> The gospels authors may have intended to write novels, myths, histories, or biographies, which are different genres and have a tremendous impact on how they ought to be interpreted. Among contemporary scholars, there is consensus that the gospels are a type of ancient biography,<ref>Stanton, G. H. (2004). ''Jesus and Gospel.'' Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. p. 192.</ref><ref>Burridge, R. A. (2006). Gospels. In J. W. Rogerson & Judith M. Lieu (Eds) ''The Oxford Handbook of Biblical Studies''. Oxford: Oxford University Press. p. 437</ref><ref>Talbert, C. H. (1977). ''What is a Gospel? The Genre of the Canonical Gospels''. Philadelphia: Fortress Press.</ref><ref>Wills, L. M. (1997). ''The Quest of the Historical Gospel: Mark, John and the Origins of the Gospel Genre''. London: Routledge. p. 10.</ref><ref>Burridge, R. A. (2004). ''What are the Gospels? A Comparison with Graeco-Roman Biography''. rev. updated edn. Grand Rapids, Michigan: Eerdmans.</ref><!-- * --> though theologian [[Rudolf Bultmann]] notes that the gospel authors had no interest in history or in a historical Jesus.{{refn|group=q|name=Bultmann}} Michael Vines, Professor of Religious Studies at [[Lees–McRae College]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lmc.edu/directory/employee/vines-michael.htm |title=Michael Vines |publisher=Lees–McRae College}}</ref> notes that the gospel of Mark may have aspects similar to a Jewish novel.<ref>{{cite book |last=Vines |first=M. E. |year=2002 |title=The Problem of the Markan Genre: The Gospel of Mark and the Jewish Novel |location=Atlanta |publisher=Society of Biblical Literature |pages=161–162 |isbn=978-1-5898-3030-1}}</ref> Some scholars have argued that the Gospels are symbolical representations of the Torah, which were written in response to the Roman occupation and the suppression of Jewish religiosity.<ref>Peter J. Tomson (2001), ''If This be from Heaven... Jesus and the New Testament Authors in Their Relationship to Judaism'', Bloomsbury</ref><ref>Dan Lioy (2007), ''Jesus as Torah in John 1–12'', Wipf and Stock Publishers</ref>

According to Paul Eddy and Gregory Boyd, mythicists argue that in the gospels "a fictitious historical narrative" was imposed on the "mythical cosmic savior figure" created by Paul.{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy_Boyd_2007"}}<!-- * -->

Robert Price notes support for the view that the gospels are a fictional composition,{{refn|group=q|name="Price2009"}} arguing that the Gospels are a type of legendary fiction{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy_Boyd2007_p314-315"}} and that the story of Jesus portrayed in the Gospels fits the [[Rank-Raglan mythotype|mythic hero archetype]].{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy_Boyd2007_p137-138"}}

Some myth proponents suggest that some parts of the New Testament were meant to appeal to [[Gentiles]] as familiar allegories rather than history.{{sfnp|Dawkins|2006|p=97}} According to Richard Carrier, the gospels are "essentially allegory and fiction".{{refn|group=q|name=Doherty2009_pvii–viii}}

==== Hebrew Bible parallels ====
Arguments drawing comparisons between the New and Old Testaments have traditionally been made by Christian theologians in defense of their teachings, but without doubting a historical Jesus.{{efn-lr|name="Comparisons"}}

Some myth proponents note that some stories in the [[New Testament]] seem to try to reinforce [[Bible prophecy|Old Testament prophecies]]{{sfnp|Dawkins|2006|p=97}} and repeat stories about figures like [[Elijah]], [[Elisha]],<ref name="brodie2012"/> [[Moses]] and [[Joshua]] in order to appeal to Jewish converts.{{sfnp|Price|2011|p=381}} Price notes that almost all the Gospel-stories have parallels in Old Testamentical and other traditions, concluding that the Gospels are no independent sources for a historical Jesus, but "legend and myth, fiction and redaction".{{sfnp|Price|2003|p=347}}

==== Greek influences ====
In ''Christ and the Caesars'' (1877), philosopher [[Bruno Bauer]] suggested that Christianity was a [[Religious syncretism|synthesis]] of the [[Stoicism]] of [[Seneca the Younger]], Greek [[Neoplatonism]], and the Jewish theology of Philo as developed by pro-Roman Jews such as [[Josephus]]. This new religion was in need of a founder and created its Christ.<ref>Moggach, Douglas. [https://books.google.com/books?id=mEQd5VP1lBIC&pg=PA184 ''The Philosophy and Politics of Bruno Bauer'']. Cambridge University Press, 2003, p. 184. *Also see Engels, Frederick. [http://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1882/05/bauer.htm "Bruno Bauer and Early Christianity"], ''Der Sozialdemokrat'', May 1882.</ref>{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2000.9.syncretism"}} In a review of Bauer's work, Robert Price notes that Bauer's basic stance regarding the Stoic tone and the fictional nature of the Gospels are still repeated in contemporary scholarship.{{refn|group=q|name="Price2009"}}

==== Weaving together various traditions ====
According to Wells, a minimally historical Jesus existed, whose teachings were preserved in the [[Q document]].{{sfnp|Wells|1999}} According to Wells, the Gospels weave together two Jesus narratives, namely Paul's mythical Jesus and the Galilean preacher of the Q document.{{sfnp|Wells|1999}} Doherty disagrees with Wells regarding this teacher of the Q-document, arguing that he was an allegoral character who [[Wisdom (personification)|personified Wisdom]] and came to be regarded as the founder of the Q-community.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Doherty|1997}} According to Doherty, Q's Jesus and Paul's Christ were combined in the [[Gospel of Mark]] by a predominantly Gentile community.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}}

=== No independent eyewitness accounts ===

==== Lack of surviving historic records ====
Mainstream biblical scholars point out that much of the writings of antiquity have been lost<ref>{{cite book|last=Allan|first=William|title=Classical Literature: A Very Short Introduction|year=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0199665457|page=15}}</ref> and that there was little written about any Jew or Christian in this period.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2012|p=44}}<ref>Timothy Barnes ''Pagan Perceptions of Christianity" in Early Christianity: Origins and Evolution to AD 600.'' 1991, p. 232 {{ISBN|0687114446}}</ref> Ehrman points out that we do not have archaeological or textual evidence for the existence of most people in the ancient world, even famous people like Pontius Pilate, whom the myth theorists agree to have existed.{{refn|group=q|name="Ehrman 2012 44"}} [[Robert Hutchinson (author)|Robert Hutchinson]] notes that this is also true of Josephus, despite the fact that he was "a personal favorite of the Roman Emperor [[Vespasian]]".<ref name="Hutchinson2015_p9">{{Cite book|title = Searching for Jesus|last = Hutchinson|first = Robert|publisher = Nelson Books|year = 2015|isbn = 978-0-7180-1830-6|location = Nashville|page = 9}}</ref> Hutchinson quotes Ehrman, who notes that Josephus is never mentioned in 1st century Greek and Roman sources, despite being "a personal friend of the emperor".<ref name="Hutchinson2015_p9"/> According to [[Classicist|Classical]] historian and popular author [[Michael Grant (author)|Michael Grant]], if the same criterion is applied to others: "We can reject the existence of a mass of pagan personages whose reality as historical figures is never questioned".{{sfnp|Grant|1995}}

Myth proponents claim there is significance in the lack of surviving historic records about Jesus of Nazareth from any non-Jewish author until the second century,<ref>[[Bart D. Ehrman]]. ''[[Did Jesus Exist? (Ehrman)|Did Jesus Exist?]]: The Historical Argument for Jesus of Nazareth'', HarperCollins, 2012, p. 47 {{ISBN|978-0-06-220460-8}}</ref>{{sfnp|Eddy|Boyd|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WgROZMp4zDMC&pg=PA165 165]}}{{refn|group=q|name="Pagan.witnesses"}} adding that Jesus left no writings or other archaeological evidence.<ref>Gerald O'Collins, ''Christology: A Biblical, Historical, and Systematic Study of Jesus.'' 2009, pp. 1–3 {{ISBN|0-19-955787-X}}</ref> Using the argument from silence, they note that Jewish philosopher [[Philo of Alexandria]] did not mention Jesus when he wrote about the cruelty of Pontius Pilate around 40 AD.<ref>Peder Borgen, ''Philo of Alexandria.'' 1997, p. 14 {{ISBN|9004103880}}</ref>

==== Josephus and Tacitus ====
There are three non-Christian sources which are typically used to study and establish the historicity of Jesus—two mentions in Josephus and one mention in the [[ancient Rome|Roman]] source [[Tacitus]].<ref name="Camber121">''The Cambridge Companion to Jesus'' by Markus N. A. Bockmuehl 2001 {{ISBN|0521796784}} pp. 121–125</ref><ref name="ChiltonEvans1998">{{cite book |author1=Bruce David Chilton |author2=Craig Alan Evans |title=Studying the Historical Jesus: Evaluations of the State of Current Research |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AJM9grxOjjMC |year=1998 |publisher=Brill |pages= 460–470 |isbn=90-04-11142-5}}</ref><ref name= Blomberg431 >''Jesus and the Gospels: An Introduction and Survey'' by Craig L. Blomberg 2009 {{ISBN|0-8054-4482-3}} pp. 431–436</ref>{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=39–53}} According to [[John Dominic Crossan]]:
{{quote|That [Jesus] was crucified is as sure as anything historical can ever be, since both Josephus and Tacitus [...] agree with the Christian accounts on at least that basic fact.{{sfnp|Crossan|1995|p=145}}}}

=====Josephus=====
{{Main|Josephus on Jesus}}

Josephus' ''Antiquities of the Jews'', written around 93–94&nbsp;AD, includes two references to the biblical Jesus in Books [[s:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XVIII#Chapter 3|18]] and [[s:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XX#Chapter 9|20]]. The general scholarly view is that while the longer passage in book 18, known as the ''Testimonium Flavianum'', is most likely not authentic in its entirety, it is broadly agreed upon that it originally consisted of an authentic nucleus, which was then subject to Christian interpolation or forgery.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schreckenberg|first=Heinz|title=Jewish Traditions in Early Christian Literature|year=1992|isbn=90-232-2653-4|author2=Kurt Schubert}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kostenberger|first=Andreas J.|title=The Cradle, the Cross, and the Crown: An Introduction to the New Testament|year=2009|isbn=0-8054-4365-7|author2=L. Scott Kellum |author3=Charles L. Quarles }}</ref>{{refn|group=q|name=Vermeer.2010.p54-55}}<!-- * --> Myth proponents also argue that the ''[[Testimonium Flavianum]]'' may have been a partial [[Interpolation (manuscripts)|interpolation]] or forgery by Christian apologist [[Eusebius]] in the 4th century or by others.<ref>Kenneth A. Olson, ''Eusebius and the Testimonium Flavianum''. The Catholic Biblical Quarterly 61 (2): 305, 1999</ref>{{sfnp|Eddy|Boyd|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WgROZMp4zDMC&pg=PA197 197 n. 103]}}{{efn-lr|One reason why Christ mythicists suspect forgery  is because the passage previous to the ''Testimonium Flavianum'' concerns Pontius Pilate setting his soldiers loose to massacre a large crowd of Jews in Jerusalem and—without the ''Testimonium Flavianum''—the following paragraph starts by saying: "[[s:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XVIII#Chapter 3|About the same time also another sad calamity put the Jews into disorder]]". They deem this suspicious as Josephus supposedly just wrote about Jesus being "the [[Christ (title)|Christ]]" and the rise of "the tribe of Christians", seeing this as not fitting in the context. {{pb}} Other reasons include the passage not being something a devout Jew such as Josephus would write (especially, "if it be lawful to call him a man" and "doer of incredible deeds"), as his writing was usually sophisticated and would have explained anything out of the ordinary to his Gentile audience, such as explaining what the word "Christ" means, why Jesus was called that and further explanations such as how he won over many Jews and Greeks, as he did for every other group (see [[s:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XVIII#Chapter 1|book 18, chapter 1]]), or why he would mention Jesus [[Resurrection of Jesus|"appearing" in the "third day"]]—a Christian creed—without explaining it{{sfnp|Maier|2007|pp=336–337}} and how no one seemed to notice this passage until the 4th century, not even [[Origen]] who quotes Josephus extensively in his works,{{sfnp|Louth|1990|}} thus leading mythicists to think that the ''Testimonium Flavianum'' is a forgery of the 4th century, perhaps written by Eusebius{{sfnp|McGiffert|2007}} in order to provide an outside Jewish authority for the life of Jesus.{{sfnp|Olson|1999}}{{sfnp|Wallace-Hadrill|2011}}}}

The other mention in Josephus is as follows:
{{quote|...the brother of Jesus, who was called Christ, whose name was James}}

According to Josephus scholar [[Louis H. Feldman]], "few have doubted the genuineness" of Josephus' reference to Jesus in [[s:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XX#Chapter 9|Antiquities 20, 9, 1]] and it is only disputed by a small number of scholars.<ref name=JospehusM662>''The new complete works of Josephus'' by Flavius Josephus, William Whiston, Paul L. Maier {{ISBN|0-8254-2924-2}} pp. 662–663</ref><ref>''Josephus XX'' by [[Louis H. Feldman]] 1965, {{ISBN|0674995023}} p. 496</ref>{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|p=83}}<ref>Flavius Josephus; Maier, Paul L. (December 1995). ''Josephus, the essential works: a condensation of Jewish antiquities and The Jewish war'' {{ISBN|978-0-8254-3260-6}} pp. 284–285</ref>

Paul Eddy and Gregory Boyd, who are critical of Christ myth theorists, note that Josephus "mentions twenty-one other people with the name Jesus,"{{efn-lr|Josephus mentions several people named Jesus ([[Jesus ben Ananias|Jesus son of Ananias]], [[Jesus son of Damneus]], Jesus son of Onias and Jesus the brother of John) as well as various [[prophet]]s, being avidly against calling any of them [[Messiah]]s, even describing them as "having evil or dishonorable intentions" and sometimes calling them "charlatans" (the [[Egyptian (prophet)|Egyptian]], the [[Samaritan]], [[Theudas]] and an unnamed "impostor"), but providing for each more information and explanations than the Jesus passage.}} and argue that when Josephus called [[James the Just|James]] the "brother" of Jesus "called Christ" in the ''Antiquities'', he did so to distinguish him "from the other persons named 'Jesus' he had already mentioned."{{sfnp|Eddy|Boyd|2007|p=189}}{{efn-lr|More specifically, from  Jesus son of Damneus, who is mentioned at the end of [[s:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XX#Chapter 9|book 20, chapter 9:1]]).{{sfnp|Eddy|Boyd|2007|p=189}}}}

Richard Carrier disagrees, proposing that the original text referred to a brother of the high priest [[Jesus son of Damneus]], named James, who is mentioned in the same narrative, in which James (the brother of Jesus) is executed by [[Ananus ben Ananus]].{{sfnp|Carrier|2012}}{{efn-lr|The Jews get angry at this, therefore complaints and demands are made, the king removes Ananus from being high priest and Jesus is then made high priest.{{sfnp|Carrier|2012}}}} Carrier further argues that the words "the one called Christ" likely resulted from the accidental insertion of a marginal note added by some unknown reader.{{sfnp|Carrier|2012}}

Others speculate that he was referring to a mythic Christ that had already been historicized, or to [[Fraternity|fraternal]] brotherhood rather than a literal sibling.<ref group=q name="mix.Price.2009.2011" /> This is dismissed by some in mainstream academia on the grounds that there is no evidence of a supposed "Jerusalem brotherhood".<ref name="Habermas">The Historical Jesus: Ancient Evidence for the Life of Christ, by Gary R. Habermas, College Press, 1996. pp. 31–35</ref>

=====Tacitus=====
{{Main|Tacitus on Christ}}

[[Roman historiography|Roman historian]] Tacitus referred to "Christus" and his execution by Pontius Pilate in his ''[[Annals (Tacitus)|Annals]]'' (written {{circa|AD 116}}), [[s:The Annals (Tacitus)/Book 15#44|book 15, chapter 44]]:<ref name="P.E. Easterling, E. J p. 892">P.E. Easterling, E. J. Kenney (general editors), ''The Cambridge History of Latin Literature'', p. 892 (Cambridge University Press, 1982, reprinted 1996). {{ISBN|0-521-21043-7}}</ref>
{{quote|...a class hated for their abominations, called Christians by the populace. Christus, from whom the name had its origin, suffered the extreme penalty during the reign of Tiberius at the hands of one of our procurators, Pontius Pilatus.<ref>Translation from Latin by [[Alfred John Church|A. J. Church]] and W. J. Brodribb, 1876</ref>}}

The very negative tone of Tacitus' comments on Christians make most experts believe that the passage is extremely unlikely to have been forged by a Christian scribe.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=39–53}} The Tacitus reference is now widely accepted as an independent confirmation of Christ's crucifixion,{{sfnp|Eddy|Boyd|2007|p=127}} although some scholars question the [[Tacitus on Christ#Authenticity and historical value|historical value of the passage]] on various grounds.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=39–53}}<ref>F.F. Bruce,''Jesus and Christian Origins Outside the New Testament'', (Grand Rapids: Eerdmans, 1974) p. 23</ref>{{sfnp|Theissen|Merz|1998|p=83}}<ref name="martin">{{cite book |first=Michael |last=Martin |title=The Case Against Christianity |pages=50–51 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=wWkC4dTmK0AC&pg=PA52&dq=historicity+of+jesus#v=onepage&q=tacitus&f=false |isbn=9781566390811 |date=1993}}</ref>{{sfnp|Weaver|1999|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1CZbuFBdAMUC&pg=PA53#v=onepage&f=false 53, 57]}}<ref name="books.google.co.za">[https://books.google.com/books?id=jCaopp3R5B0C&pg=PA100&dq=interpolations+in+tacitus&hl=en&sa=X&ei=CRf-U9-VGZCe7AbxrIDQCA&ved=0CCAQ6AEwATge#v=onepage&q=interpolations%20in%20tacitus&f=false ''Secret of Regeneration''], by Hilton Hotema, p. 100</ref><ref>''Jesus'', University Books, New York, 1956, p. 13</ref><ref>{{Cite book|authorlink=R. T. France|last=France|first=R. T.|title=Evidence for Jesus (Jesus Library)|publisher=Trafalgar Square Publishing|year=1986|isbn=0-340-38172-8|pages=19–20}}</ref>

Christ myth theory supporters such as G. A. Wells and Carrier contend that sources such as Tacitus and others, which were written decades after the supposed events, include no independent traditions that relate to Jesus, and hence can provide no confirmation of historical facts about him.{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst2000_p13"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Lataster2015_p68"}}

====Other sources====
In ''Jesus Outside the New Testament'' (2000), mainstream scholar Van Voorst considers references to Jesus in classical writings, Jewish writings, hypothetical sources of the canonical Gospels, and extant Christian writings outside the New Testament. Van Voorst concludes that non-Christian sources provide "a small but certain corroboration of certain New Testament historical traditions on the family background, time of life, ministry, and death of Jesus", as well as "evidence of the content of Christian preaching that is independent of the New Testament", while extra-biblical Christian sources give access to "some important information about the earliest traditions on Jesus". However, New Testament sources remain central for "both the main lines and the details about Jesus' life and teaching".{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|p=217}}</ref>

===Diversity and parallels===
{{See also|Origins of Christianity|Gnosticism}}

====Early Christian diversity points to multiple roots====
{{See also|Diversity in early Christian theology}}
Early Christianity was wildly diverse, with proto-orthodoxy and "[[Heresy|heretical]]" views like gnosticism alongside each other.{{sfnp|Pagels|1979}}{{sfnp|Ehrman|2003|ps=none}} According to Mack, various "Jesus movements" existed, whose ideas converged in an early proto-orthodoxy.{{sfnp|Mack|1995|ps=none}}

According to Doherty, the rapid growth of early Christian communities and the great variety of ideas cannot be explained by a single missionary effort, but points to parallel developments, which arose at various places and competed for support. Paul's arguments against rival apostles also point to this diversity.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} Doherty further notes that [[Yeshua]] (Jesus) is a generic name, meaning "Yahweh saves" and refers to the concept of divine salvation, which could apply to any kind of saving entity or Wisdom.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}}

==== Parallels with other religions ====
{{See also|Religious syncretism|Mytheme}}

Doherty notes that, with the conquests of [[Alexander the Great]], the [[Ancient Greece|Greek culture]] and [[Ancient Greek|language]] spread throughout the eastern Mediterranean world, influencing the already existing cultures there.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} The Roman conquest of this area added to the cultural diversity, but also to a sense of alienation and pessimism.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} A rich diversity of religious and philosophical ideas was available and [[Judaism]] was held in high regard by non-Jews for its monotheistic ideas and its high moral standards.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} Yet [[monotheism]] was also offered by Greek philosophy, especially [[Platonism]], with its high God and the intermediary [[Logos]].{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} According to Doherty, "Out of this rich soil of ideas arose Christianity, a product of both Jewish and Greek philosophy",{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} echoing Bruno Bauer, who argued that Christianity was a synthesis of Stoicism, Greek Neoplatonism and Jewish thought.{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2000.9.syncretism"}}

===== Jewish belief in a celestial angel called Jesus =====
Mainstream scholars have noted the extent and significance of Jewish belief in a chief angel acting as a heavenly mediator during the [[Second Temple period]],{{refn|group=q| name="Jewish angel"}} as well as the similarities between Jesus and this chief celestial angel.{{refn|group=q|name="Barker.1992.p190-233"}} Ehrman has even gone so far as to argue that Paul regarded Jesus to be an angel, who was incarnated on earth.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2014|ps=none}}{{efn-lr|name=Ehrman_angel|Ehrman-blog, [https://ehrmanblog.org/pauls-christology/ ''Paul’s View of Jesus as an Angel'']: "Paul understood Christ to be an angel who became a human." See also [https://ehrmanblog.org/pauls-view-of-jesus-as-an-angel-for-members/ ''Paul’s View of Jesus as an Angel''], [https://ehrmanblog.org/christ-as-an-angel-in-paul-for-members/ ''Christ as an Angel in Paul'' (10 april 2014)], [https://ehrmanblog.org/christ-as-an-angel-in-paul-2/ ''Christ as an Angel in Paul'' (7 juni 2014)]; and Carrier's response at [https://www.richardcarrier.info/archives/6923 ''Bart Ehrman on How Jesus Became God''].}}

According to Carrier, originally "Jesus was the name of a celestial being, subordinate to God".<ref name="Carrier.2012.where.did.he.come.from"/> According to Carrier, "This 'Jesus' would most likely have been the same archangel identified by Philo of Alexandria as already extant in Jewish theology".<ref>{{harvp|Carrier|2014|pp=200–205}}{{bulleted list |Jesus being a preexisting archangel: Phil. 2:5–11 |Jesus was as an angel: Gal. 4:14 |Jesus knew Moses: 1 Cor. 10:4}}</ref> Philo knew this figure by all of the attributes Paul already knew Jesus by: the firstborn son of God ([[Epistle to the Romans]] 8:29), the celestial image of God ([[Second Epistle to the Corinthians]] 4:4) and God's agent of creation ([[First Epistle to the Corinthians]] 8:6). He was also God's celestial high priest (Hebrews 2:17, 4:14, etc.) and God's Logos. Philo says this being was identified as the figure named Jesus in the [[Book of Zechariah]].{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier.Zechariah.6"}}

===== Personification of Logos and Wisdom =====
Separately from mythicism, scholar of ancient religious studies [[Peter Schäfer]] contends that Philo's Logos was likely derived from his understanding of the "postbiblical Wisdom literature, in particular the Wisdom of Solomon".{{refn|group=q|name="Schäfer.2011.p159"}} Professor of New Testament at Loyola University Urban C. von Wahlde notes that the Wisdom literature and the philosophical writings of Philo may furnish "the background to the Logos of the [[Johannine epistles|Johannine]] Prologue".{{refn|group=q|name="Wahlde.2015.p171"}}

According to mythicists, Christianity originated from a Jewish [[sect]]{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Price.2010.103.Price.2002"}} in a [[Social environment|milieu]] where some [[Jews]] practised a form of proto-gnosticism{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}—seeking salvation by revealed [[gnosis]]—via a mediator between God and humans, i.e. an intermediary variously known as "one like a son of man", "the divine Logos", etc. From the cultus of Paul, a divergent form of this salvation theology was later promoted for non-Jews.{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Lataster.2016.Carrier.2016"}}{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Doherty.2009.1996.2012"}}{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Price.2000.79.Doherty.2000"}}{{refn|group=q|name="mix.Wells.1999.97.Doherty.2012"}}

According to Doherty, a somewhat similar idea to the Greek Logos was found in Judaism, where [[Biblical cosmology#Naming: God, Wisdom, Torah and Christ|Wisdom]], a personified part of God, brought knowledge of God and the Law.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} Similar ideas were also developed in other cultures and religions.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995c|ps=none}} According to Wells, the historical Jesus was derived from this Wisdom traditions, the personification of an eternal aspect of God, who came to visit human beings.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2012|p=349, n. 20}} Doherty notes that the concept of a spiritual Christ was the result of common philosophical and religious ideas of the first and second century AD, in which the idea of an intermediary force between God and the world were common.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}} Doherty further notes that [[divine inspiration]] was a common concept.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}}

===== Jewish-Hellenistic mystery cult =====
According to Doherty, the Christ of Paul shares similarities with the [[Greco-Roman mysteries|Greco-Roman mystery cults]].{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}} Authors Timothy Freke and [[Peter Gandy (author)|Peter Gandy]] explicitly argue that Jesus was a deity, akin to the mystery cults,{{sfnp|Freke|Gandy|1999}} while [[Acharya S|Dorothy Murdock]] argues that the Christ myth draws heavily on the Egyptian story of [[Osiris]] and [[Horus]].<ref name="Christ in Egypt">{{cite web |last1=Price |first1=Robert M. |title=Book review of D.M. Murdock (Acharya S.), ''Christ in Egypt: The Horus-Jesus Connection''. Stellar House Publishing. |website=r m p Reviews | url =http://www.robertmprice.mindvendor.com/reviews/murdock_christ_egypt.htm |accessdate=August 4, 2010 |date=2009 }}</ref> According to Robert Price, the story of Jesus portrayed in the Gospels is akin to the [[Rank-Raglan mythotype|mythic hero archetype]].{{refn|group=q|name="Eddy_Boyd2007_p137-138"}} The mythic hero archetype is present in many cultures who often have miraculous conceptions or virgin births heralded by wise men and marked by a star, are tempted by or fight evil forces, die on a hill, appear after death and then ascend to heaven.{{sfnp|Price|2011|p=425}} According to Carrier, early Christianity was but one of several mystery cults which developed out of Hellenistic influences on local cults and religions.<ref name="Carrier.2012.where.did.he.come.from"/>

Mainstream scholarship disagrees with this interpretation. Many mainstream biblical scholars respond that most of these parallels are either coincidences or without historical basis and/or that these parallels do not prove that a Jesus figure did not live.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2012|p=208}}{{efn-lr|In particular, the transformations faced by deities have distinct differences from the resurrection of Jesus.  [[Osiris]] regains consciousness as king of the underworld, rather than being "transformed into an eschatological new creation" as [[Craig S. Keener]] writes.<ref name="Keener">The Historical Jesus of the Gospels, by Craig S. Keener, Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2012. p. 336</ref>  While Jesus was born from a human woman (traditionally a virgin) and accompanied by shepherds, [[Mitra]] is born (unaccompanied by shepherds) from the goddess [[Aditi]] (to whom the word "virgin" is only rarely, loosely, and indirectly applied in a highly poetic sense), while [[Mithras]] (granted, accompanied by shepherds later) emerges full-grown from a rock.{{sfnp|Casey|2014|p=155}} The rebirth of many of these deities was a clear metaphor for the renewal of spring that repeated the death every year, rather than a historic event meant to proclaim the god's cancellation of death. Some of these parallels appear after Christianity (e.g. the earliest references to [[Adonis]] rising from the dead is in the second century AD, [[Attis]] a century later), and are often only known through later Christian sources. Most other and later parallels were made in the works of [[James George Frazer]],<ref name="Keener" /> or may be guilty of [[parallelomania]]<ref>Jesus and His Contemporaries: Comparative Studies, by Craig A. Evans, Brill,  2001. p. 48</ref> and even misrepresentation of religious (both Christian and non-Christian) and linguistic sources<ref name="Keener" />{{sfnp|Casey|2014|p=206}} (for example, ignoring the [[false cognate]] relationship between Christ and [[Krishna]]).{{sfnp|Casey|2014|p=206}}}} Christian theologians have cited the mythic hero archetype as a defense of Christian teaching while completely affirming a historical Jesus.<ref name="Ramshaw">What Is Christianity?: An Introduction to the Christian Religion, by Gail Ramshaw, Fortress Press, 2013. pp. 52–54</ref><ref name="Benson">God and Caesar: Troeltsch's Social Teaching as Legitimation, by Constance L. Benson, Transaction Publishers. p. 55</ref>{{efn-lr|Some have even identified the historical and archetypal Jesuses<ref name="Benson" /> or citing Carl Jung's statement "this Christ of St. Paul's would hardly have been possible without the historical Jesus."<ref name="Ramshaw" />}} Secular academics have also pointed out that the teachings of Jesus marked "a radical departure from all the conventions by which heroes had been defined".<ref>The Heroic Ideal: Western Archetypes from the Greeks to the Present, by M. Gregory Kendrick, McFarland, 2010. p. 43</ref>

== 18th- and 19th-century proponents ==
[[File:Constantin François Volney 1.jpg|upright=0.6|thumb|alt=a sketch of a bust of Constantin-François Chassebœuf|French historian [[Constantin-François Chassebœuf|Constantin-François Volney]], one of the earliest myth theorists]]

According to Van Voorst, "The argument that Jesus never existed, but was invented by the Christian movement around the year 100, goes back to Enlightenment times, when the historical-critical study of the past was born," and may have originated with Lord Bolingbroke, an English deist.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|p=568}}

According to Weaver and Schneider, the beginnings of the formal denial of the existence of Jesus can be traced to late 18th-century France with the works of [[Constantin-François Chassebœuf|Constantin François Chassebœuf de Volney]] and [[Charles-François Dupuis]].{{sfnp|Weaver|1999|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1CZbuFBdAMUC&pg=PA45#v=onepage&f=false 45–50]}}{{sfnp|Schweitzer|2001|pp=355ff}} Volney and Dupuis argued that Christianity was an amalgamation of various ancient mythologies and that Jesus was a totally mythical character.{{sfnp|Weaver|1999|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1CZbuFBdAMUC&pg=PA45#v=onepage&f=false 45–50]}}{{sfnp|Voorst|2000|p=8}} Dupuis argued that ancient rituals in Syria, Egypt, Mesopotamia, Persia, and India had influenced the Christian story which was [[allegory|allegorized]] as the histories of [[solar deity|solar deities]], such as [[Sol Invictus]].{{sfnp|Wells|1969|p=}} Dupuis also said that the resurrection of Jesus was an allegory for the growth of the sun's strength in the sign of Aries at the spring [[equinox]].{{sfnp|Wells|1969|p=}} Volney argued that [[Abraham]] and [[Sarah]] were derived from [[Brahma]] and his wife [[Saraswati]], whereas Christ was related to [[Krishna]].<ref name=Leask104>''British Romantic Writers and the East'' by Nigel Leask (2004) {{ISBN|0521604443}} Cambridge Univ Press pp. 104–105</ref><ref>{{cite book |author-link=Tristram Stuart |first=Tristram |last=Stuart |title=The Bloodless Revolution |publisher=W. W. Norton |year=2007 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Bloodless_Revolution.html?id=mVJA5Z7CRHMC&printsec=frontcover&source=kp_read_button#v=onepage&q=volney&f=false |page=591 |isbn=978-0-3930-5220-6 |access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Volney made use of a draft version of Dupuis' work and at times differed from him, e.g. in arguing that the gospel stories were not intentionally created, but were compiled organically.{{sfnp|Wells|1969|p=}} Volney's perspective became associated with the ideas of the [[French Revolution]], which hindered the acceptance of these views in [[England]].<ref name=Prickett>{{cite encyclopedia |author=Stephen Prickett |encyclopedia=Companion Encyclopedia of Theology |editor1=Peter Byrne |editor2=James Leslie Houlden |year=1995 |isbn=0415064473 |pages=154–155}}</ref> Despite this, his work gathered significant following among British and American radical thinkers during the 19th century.<ref name=Prickett/>

[[File:1908 David-Friedrich-Strauss.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.6|alt=portrait|German Professor [[David Strauss]]]]
In 1835, German theologian [[David Strauss|David Friedrich Strauss]] published his extremely controversial ''The Life of Jesus, Critically Examined'' (''Das Leben Jesu''). While not denying that Jesus existed, he did argue that the miracles in the New Testament were mythical retellings of normal events as supernatural happenings.<ref>''The Life of Jesus, Critically Examined'' by David Friedrich Strauss 2010 {{ISBN|1-61640-309-8}} pp. 39–43, 87–91</ref><ref>''The Making of the New Spirituality'' by James A. Herrick 2003 {{ISBN|0-8308-2398-0}} pp. 58–65</ref><ref name=Fami81>''Familiar Stranger: An Introduction to Jesus of Nazareth'' by Michael J. McClymond (2004) {{ISBN|0802826806}} p. 82</ref> According to Strauss, the early church developed these miracle stories to present Jesus as a fulfillment of Jewish prophecies of what the Messiah would be like. This [[rationalist]] perspective was in direct opposition to the [[supernaturalism|supernaturalist]] view that the bible was accurate both historically and spiritually. The book caused an uproar across Europe, as [[Anthony Ashley-Cooper, 7th Earl of Shaftesbury]] called it "the most pestilential book ever vomited out of the jaws of hell"<ref name=Dawes77 >''The historical Jesus question'' by Gregory W. Dawes 2001 {{ISBN|0-664-22458-X}} pp. 77–79</ref> and Strauss' appointment as chair of theology at the [[University of Zürich]] caused such controversy that the authorities offered him a pension before he had a chance to start his duties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chora-strangers.org/article/mcgaughey1994 |author=Douglas R McGaughey |date=1994 |title=On D.F. Strauß and the 1839 Revolution in Zurich |website=Chora Strangers |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201204703/http://www.chora-strangers.org/article/mcgaughey1994 |archive-date=February 1, 2014 }}</ref>

[[File:Bruno Bauer.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|alt=portrait|German Professor [[Bruno Bauer]]]]
German Bruno Bauer, who taught at the [[University of Bonn]], took Strauss' arguments further and became the first author to systematically argue that Jesus did not exist.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=7–11}}<ref name="BeilbyEddy2009">Beilby, James K. and Eddy, Paul Rhodes. [https://books.google.com/books?id=O33P7xrFnLQC&pg=PA16 "The Quest for the Historical Jesus"], in James K. Beilby and Paul Rhodes Eddy (eds.). ''The Historical Jesus: Five Views''. Intervarsity, 2009, p. 16.
* See Strauss, David. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=RmdLqnfw1OgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Strauss+Jesus&hl=en&ei=TKNUTIT8MIShnAfxiYWMBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false "The Life of Jesus Critically Examined]'', Calvin Blanchard, 1860.</ref> Beginning in 1841 with his ''Criticism of the Gospel History of the Synoptics'', Bauer argued that Jesus was primarily a literary figure, but left open the question of whether a historical Jesus existed at all. Then in his ''Criticism of the Pauline Epistles'' (1850–1852) and in ''A Critique of the Gospels and a History of their Origin'' (1850–1851), Bauer argued that Jesus had not existed.{{sfnp|Schweitzer|2001|pp=124–128, 139–141}} Bauer's work was heavily criticized at the time, as in 1839 he was removed from his position at the University of Bonn and his work did not have much impact on future myth theorists.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=7–11}}{{sfnp|Bennett|2001|p=204}}

In his two-volume, 867-page book ''[[Anacalypsis]]'' (1836), English gentleman [[Godfrey Higgins]] said that "the mythos of the Hindus, the mythos of the Jews and the mythos of the Greeks are all at bottom the same; and are contrivances under the appearance of histories to perpetuate doctrines"{{sfnp|Harpur|2004|p=30}} and that Christian editors “either from roguery or folly, corrupted them all”.{{sfnp|Harpur|2004|p=59}} In his 1875 book ''[[The World's Sixteen Crucified Saviors]]'', American [[Kersey Graves]] said that many demigods from different countries shared similar stories, traits or quotes as Jesus and he used Higgins as the main source for his arguments. The validity of the claims in the book have been greatly criticized by Christ myth proponents like Richard Carrier and largely dismissed by biblical scholars.<ref>[http://infidels.org/library/modern/richard_carrier/graves.html Kersey Graves and The World's Sixteen Crucified Saviors] by Richard Carrier (2003)</ref>

Starting in the 1870s, English poet and author [[Gerald Massey]] became interested in Egyptology and reportedly taught himself Egyptian hieroglyphics at the British Museum.{{sfnp|Harpur|2004}} In 1883, Massey published ''The Natural Genesis'' where he asserted parallels between Jesus and the Egyptian god [[Horus]]. His other major work, ''Ancient Egypt: The Light of the World,'' was published shortly before his death in 1907. His assertions have influenced various later writers such as [[Alvin Boyd Kuhn]] and [[Tom Harpur]].{{sfnp|Harpur|2004|p=200}} Despite criticisms from Stanley Porter and Ward Gasque, Massey's theories regarding Egyptian etymologies for certain scriptures are supported by noted contemporary Egyptologists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomharpur.com/documentary-afterword.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513171957/http://www.tomharpur.com/documentary-afterword.asp|archivedate=May 13, 2008|title=Biography – Tom Harpur – The Official Website|date=May 13, 2008|publisher=}}</ref>

In the 1870s and 1880s, a group of scholars associated with the [[University of Amsterdam]], known in German scholarship as the Radical Dutch school, rejected the authenticity of the Pauline epistles and took a generally negative view of the Bible's historical value.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|p=10}} [[Abraham Dirk Loman]] argued in 1881 that all New Testament writings belonged to the 2nd century and doubted that Jesus was a historical figure, but later said the core of the gospels was genuine.{{sfnp|Schweitzer|2001|pp=356–361, 527 n. 4}}

Additional early Christ myth proponents included Swiss skeptic Rudolf Steck,<ref>Arthur Drew, 1926, ''The Denial of the Historicity of Jesus in Past and Present''</ref> English historian [[Edwin Johnson (historian)|Edwin Johnson]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/antiquamaterast01johngoog|title=Antiqua Mater: A Study of Christian Origins|last=Edwin Johnson|date=1887|publisher=Trübner|language=English}}</ref> English radical [[Robert Taylor (Radical)|Reverend Robert Taylor]] and his associate [[Richard Carlile]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Patrick|title=Paul as a Problem in History and Culture: The Apostle and His Critics through the Centuries|publisher=Baker Academic|isbn=9781493403332|page=85|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BQ4_CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT85|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lockley|first1=Philip|title=Visionary Religion and Radicalism in Early Industrial England: From Southcott to Socialism|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=9780199663873|page=168|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=scL4a56tdM0C&pg=PA168|language=en}}</ref>

== Early-20th-century proponents ==
During the early 20th century, several writers published arguments against Jesus' historicity, often drawing on the work of liberal theologians, who tended to deny any value to sources for Jesus outside the New Testament and limited their attention to Mark and the hypothetical [[Q source]].{{sfnp|Schweitzer|2001|pp=356–361, 527 n. 4}} They also made use of the growing field of [[History of religions|religious history]] which found sources for Christian ideas in Greek and Oriental mystery cults, rather than Judaism.<ref>Arvidsson, Stefan. ''Aryan Idols: Indo-European Mythology as Ideology and Science''. University of Chicago Press, 2006, pp. 116–117.</ref> [[Joseph Klausner]] wrote that biblical scholars "tried their hardest to find in the historic Jesus something which is not Judaism; but in his actual history they have found nothing of this whatever, since this history is reduced almost to zero. It is therefore no wonder that at the beginning of this century there has been a revival of the eighteenth and nineteenth century view that Jesus never existed".<ref>Klausner, Joseph. ''Jesus of Nazareth''. Bloch, 1989; first published 1925, pp. 105–106.</ref>

The work of social anthropologist [[Sir James George Frazer]] has had an influence on various myth theorists, although Frazer himself believed that Jesus existed.{{sfnp|Bennett|2001|p=205}} In 1890, Frazer published the first edition of ''[[The Golden Bough]]'' which attempted to define the shared elements of religious belief. This work became the basis of many later authors who argued that the story of Jesus was a fiction created by Christians. After a number of people claimed that he was a myth theorist, in the 1913 expanded edition of ''The Golden Bough'' he expressly stated that his theory assumed a historical Jesus.{{sfnp|Price|2000|p=207}}

In 1900, Scottish Member of Parliament [[J. M. Robertson|John Mackinnon Robertson]] argued that Jesus never existed, but was an invention by a first-century messianic cult.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=11–12}}{{sfnp|Wells|1987|pp=162–163}} In Robertson's view, religious groups invent new gods to fit the needs of the society of the time.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=11–12}} Robertson argued that a solar deity symbolized by the lamb and the ram had long been worshiped by an Israelite cult of Joshua and that this cult had then invented a new messianic figure, Jesus of Nazareth.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=11–12}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1900|p=34}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1902|p=72}} Robertson argued that a possible source for the Christian myth may have been the Talmudic story of the executed [[Yeshu|Jesus Pandera]] which dates to 100 BC.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=11–12}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1902|pp=6–12, 14–15}} Robertson considered the letters of Paul the earliest surviving Christian writings, but viewed them as primarily concerned with theology and morality, rather than historical details. Robertson viewed references to the twelve apostles and the institution of the [[Eucharist]] as stories that must have developed later among gentile believers who were converted by Jewish evangelists like Paul.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|pp=11–12}}{{sfnp|Robertson|1902|p=18}}{{sfnp|Wells|1987|p=149}}

The English school master [[G. R. S. Mead|George Robert Stowe Mead]] argued in 1903 that Jesus had existed, but that he had lived in 100 BC.<ref name=MeadQ>''G. R. S. Mead and the Gnostic Quest'' by Clare Goodrick-Clarke (2005) {{ISBN|155643572X}} pp. 1–3</ref>{{sfnp|Price|2009|pp=80–81}} Mead based his argument on the Talmud, which pointed to Jesus being crucified {{circa|100 BC}}. In Mead's view, this would mean that the Christian gospels are mythical.<ref>''Did Jesus Live 100 B.C.?'' by [[G. R. S. Mead]] (1903) {{ISBN|1596053763}} (Cosimo Classics 2005) pp. 10–12</ref> [[Tom Harpur]] has compared Mead's impact on myth theory to that of Bruno Bauer and Arthur Drews.<ref>''Pagan Christ: Is Blind Faith Killing Christianity?'' by Tom Harpur (2006) {{ISBN|0802777414}} p. 163</ref>

In 1909, school teacher [[John Remsburg|John Eleazer Remsburg]] published ''The Christ'', which made a distinction between a possible historical Jesus (Jesus of Nazareth) and the Jesus of the Gospels (Jesus of Bethlehem). Remsburg thought that there was good reason to believe that the historical Jesus existed, but that the "Christ of Christianity" was a mythological creation.<ref>''The Christ'' by John Remsburg 1909, Chapter 1: "Christ's Real Existence Impossible"</ref> Remsburg compiled a list of 42 names of "writers who lived and wrote during the time, or within a century after the time" who Remsburg felt should have written about Jesus if the Gospels account was reasonably accurate, but who did not.<ref>''The Christ Myth'' by John Remsburg 1909, Chapter 2: "Silence of Contemporary Writers"</ref><ref name="Fable">{{cite journal | journal = Free Inquiry | volume = 34 | issue = 5 | year = 2014 | page = 56 | title = The Fable of the Christ | last = Paulkovich | first = Michael | url = http://www.secularhumanism.org/index.php/articles/5656 | accessdate = }}</ref><ref name="Paulkovich">{{cite book |title=Beyond the Crusades|last=Paulkovich |first=Michael |year=2016 |publisher=[[American Atheists|American Atheist Press]] |isbn=978-1-5788-4037-3 |pages=267–2805}}</ref>

[[File:Arthur Drews.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|alt=portrait|German Professor [[Arthur Drews]]]]
Also in 1909, German philosophy Professor [[Arthur Drews|Christian Heinrich Arthur Drews]] wrote ''[[The Christ Myth]]'' to argue that Christianity had been a Jewish Gnostic cult that spread by appropriating aspects of Greek philosophy and life-death-rebirth deities.<ref>Drews' book was reviewed by A. Kampmeier in ''[[The Monist]]'', volume 21, Number 3 (July 1911), pp. 412–432. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/27900331?&Search=yes&searchText=myth&searchText=Christ&searchText=theory&list=hide&searchUri=%2Faction%2FdoBasicSearch%3FQuery%3DChrist%2Bmyth%2Btheory%26gw%3Djtx%26prq%3DJosephus%2BAntiquities%26hp%3D25%26wc%3Don&prevSearch=&item=22&ttl=18632&returnArticleService=showFullText]</ref> In his later books ''The Witnesses to the Historicity of Jesus'' (1912) and ''[[The Denial of the Historicity of Jesus in Past and Present]]'' (1926), Drews reviewed the biblical scholarship of his time as well as the work of other myth theorists, attempting to show that everything reported about the historical Jesus had a mythical character.{{sfnp|Weaver|1999|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1CZbuFBdAMUC&pg=PA50 50], [https://books.google.com/books?id=1CZbuFBdAMUC&pg=PA300 300]}}
* Also see Wood, Herbert George: ''Christianity and the Nature of History''. Cambridge University Press, 1934, p. xxxii.
* Arthur Drews: ''Die Christusmythe''. Eugen Diederichs, 1910, published in English as ''The Christ Myth'', Prometheus, 1910, p. 410.</ref> Drews met with criticism from [[Nikolai Berdyaev]] who claimed that Drews was an [[antisemitism|anti-Semite]] who argued against the historical existence of Jesus for the sake of [[Aryan race|Aryanism]].<ref>[[Nikolai Berdyaev]]: "The Scientific Discipline of Religion and Christian Apologetics", ''Put' / Путь'', vol. 6, 1927.</ref> Drews took part in a series of public debates with theologians and historians who opposed his arguments.<ref>Brian A. Gerrish:
[https://www.jstor.org/pss/1202070 "Jesus, Myth, and History: Troeltsch's Stand in the 'Christ-Myth' Debate"], ''The Journal of Religion'', vol. 55,  issue 1, 1975, pp. 3–4.</ref><ref name=DrewsNYT>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/02/06/102035055.pdf "Jesus never lived, asserts Prof. Drews"], ''The New York Times'', February 6, 1910.</ref>

Drews' work found fertile soil in the [[Soviet Union]], where [[Marxist–Leninist atheism]] was the official doctrine of the state. Soviet leader [[Lenin]] argued that it was imperative in the struggle against religious obscurantists to form a union with people like Drews.<ref>James Thrower: ''Marxist-Leninist "Scientific Atheism" and the Study of Religion and Atheism''. [[Walter de Gruyter]], 1983, p. 426.
* Also see Edyth C. Haber: [http://jstor.org/stable/309549 "The Mythic Bulgakov: 'The Master and Margarita' and Arthur Drews's 'The Christ Myth'"], ''Slavic & East European Journal'', vol. 43, issue 2, 1999, p. 347.</ref> Several editions of Drews' ''The Christ Myth'' were published in the Soviet Union from the early 1920s onwards and his arguments were included in school and university textbooks.<ref>Nikiforov, Vladimir. "Russian Christianity", in James Leslie Houlden (ed.) ''Jesus in History, Thought, and Culture: An Encyclopedia''. ABC-CLIO, 2003, p. 749.</ref> Public meetings asking "Did Christ live?" were organized, during which party operatives debated with clergymen.<ref>Peris, Daniel. ''Storming the Heavens''. [[Cornell University Press]], 1998, p. 178.</ref>

In 1927, British philosopher [[Bertrand Russell]] stated in his lecture ''[[Why I Am Not a Christian]]'' that "historically it is quite doubtful that Jesus existed, and if he did we do not know anything about him, so that I am not concerned with the historical question, which is a very difficult one", though Russell did nothing to further develop the idea.<ref>Russell, Bertrand. [http://users.drew.edu/~jlenz/whynot.html "Why I am not a Christian"], lecture to the National Secular Society, Battersea Town Hall, March 6, 1927, Retrieved August 2, 2010.</ref>

[[Church of Scientology]] founder [[L. Ron Hubbard]] was convinced that Jesus never existed, stating that Christianity evolved from the "[[Xenu|R6 Implant]]": "The man on the cross. There was no Christ! The [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic Church]], through watching the dramatizations of people picked up some little fragments of R6".<ref>{{cite book | last =Corydon  | first =Bent  |author2=Brian Ambry | title =[[L. Ron Hubbard: Messiah or Madman?]] | publisher =Barricade Books | year =1992 | page =353 | isbn = 0-942637-57-7}}</ref>

== Modern proponents ==

=== Paul-Louis Couchoud ===
The French philosopher Paul-Louis Couchoud,{{sfnp|Weaver|1999|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1CZbuFBdAMUC&pg=PA300 300–303]}} published in the 1920s and 1930s, but was a predecessor for contemporary mythicists.{{refn|group=q|name="vridar_Couchoud"}} According to Couchoud, Christianity started not with a biography of Jesus but "a collective mystical experience, sustaining a divine history mystically revealed."{{refn|group=q|name="Couchoud1926_p23"}} Couchaud's Jesus is not a "myth", but a "religious conception".<ref name="Hibbert1939">''Hibbert Journal'' Volume 37 (1938–39), pp. 193–214</ref>

Robert Price mentions Couchoud's comment on the Christ Hymn, one of the relics of the Christ cults to which Paul converted. Couchoud noted that in this hymn the name Jesus was given to the Christ after his torturous death, implying that there cannot have been a ministry by a teacher called Jesus.<ref name="Price.2003.Name" />

=== George Albert Wells ===
[[George Albert Wells]] (1926–2017), a professor of German, revived the interest in the Christ myth theory. In his early work,<ref>{{harvp|Wells|1971}}, {{harvp|Wells|1975}}, {{harvp|Wells|1982}}</ref> including ''[[Did Jesus Exist? (Wells)|Did Jesus Exist?]]'' (1975), Wells argued that because the Gospels were written decades after Jesus's death by Christians who were theologically motivated but had no personal knowledge of him, a rational person should believe the gospels only if they are independently confirmed.<ref name="Martin.1993.p38">{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Michael|title=The Case Against Christianity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wWkC4dTmK0AC&pg=PA38 |date=1993 |publisher=Temple University Press|isbn=978-1-56639-081-1|page=38}}</ref> Wells was featured in the controversial UK television programme series, ''[[Jesus: The Evidence]]'' (Channel 4: 1984), which caused a furore, being Channel 4's first major religious programme commission.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wallis|first=Richard|date=January 27, 2016|title=Channel 4 and the declining influence of organized religion on UK television. The case of Jesus: The Evidence|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/01439685.2015.1132821|journal=Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television|language=en|volume=36|issue=4|pages=668–688|doi=10.1080/01439685.2015.1132821|issn=0143-9685}}</ref>

Atheist philosopher and scholar [[Michael Martin (philosopher)|Michael Martin]] supported his thesis, claiming: "Jesus is not placed in a historical context and the biographical details of his life are left unsuspecte [...] a strong prima facie case challenging the historicity of Jesus can be constructed".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Habermas|first1=Gary R|title=The Historical Jesus: Ancient Evidence for the Life of Christ|date=1996|publisher=College Pr Pub Co; Subsequent edition|isbn=0-8990-0732-5|pages=37–38}}</ref> Martin adds in his book ''The Case Against Christianity'' that "Well's argument against the historicity [of Jesus] is sound".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Martin |first1=Michael |title=The Case Against Christianity |date=1993 |publisher=Temple University Press |isbn=1566390818 |page=67}}</ref>

Later, Wells concluded that a historical Jesus figure did exist and was a Galilean preacher, whose teachings were preserved in the Q document, a hypothetical common source for the gospels of Matthew and Luke.{{refn|group=q|name="Wells_historicity"}} However, he continued to insist that Biblical Jesus did not exist and argued that stories such as the virgin birth, the crucifixion around A.D. 30 under Pilate and the resurrection should be regarded as legendary.{{sfnp|Wells|1999}}{{refn|group=q|name="Wells.Jesus.Down.Size"}}{{efn-lr|For a more brief statement of his position, Wells refers readers to his article, "Jesus, Historicity of" in Tom Flynn's ''The New Encyclopedia of Unbelief''. Prometheus Books, 2007, pp. 446ff. Per Wells, G. A. ''Cutting Jesus Down to Size''. Open Court, 2009, pp. 327–328.}} Biblical scholar [[Robert E. Van Voorst]] said that with this argument Wells had performed an about-face.{{refn|group=q|name="Voorst.2003.p660"}} However, other scholars continue to note Wells as a mythicist.{{refn|group=q|name=mix.Doherty.Wells}}

In his 2009 book ''Cutting Jesus Down to Size'',{{sfnp|Wells|2009}} Wells clarified that he believes the Gospels represent the fusion of two originally independent streams: a Galilean preaching tradition and the supernatural personage of Paul's early epistles, but he says that both figures owe much of their substance to ideas from the Jewish wisdom literature.{{refn|group=q|name="Wells2013_p16"}}

In 2000 Van Voorst gave an overview of proponents of the "Nonexistence Hypothesis" and their arguments, and eight arguments against this hypothesis as put forward by Wells and his predecessors:{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|p=14-15}}{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2003|p=659–660}}
# The "argument of silence" is to be rejected, because "it is wrong to suppose that what is unmentioned or undetailed did not exist." Van Voorst further argues that the early Christian literature was not written for historical purposes.
# Dating the "invention" of Jesus around 100 CE is too late; Mark was written earlier, and contains abundant historical details which are correct.
# The argument that the development of the Gospel traditions shows that there was no historical Jesus is incorrect; "development does not prove wholesale invention, and difficulties do not prove invention."
# Wells cannot explain why "no pagans and Jews who opposed Christianity denied Jesus' historicity or even questioned it."
# The rejection of Tacitus and Josephus ignores the scholarly consensus.
# Proponents of the "Nonexistence Hypothesis" are not driven by scholarly interests, but by anti-Christian sentiments.
# Wells and others do not offer alternative "other, credible hypotheses" for the origins of Christianity.
# Wells himself accepted the existence of a minimal historical Jesus, thereby effectively leaving the "Nonexistence Hypothesis."

According to Graham Stanton, writing in 2002, Wells advanced the most sophisticated version of the Christ myth theory, noting that "[t]his intriguing theory rests on several pillars, each of which is shaky."{{Sfnp|Stanton|2002|pp=143ff}} According to Maurice Casey, Wells' work repeated the main points of the ''Religionsgeschichtliche Schule'', which are deemed outdated by mainstream scholarship. His works were not discussed by New Testament scholars, because it was "not considered to be original, and all his main points were thought to have been refuted long time ago, for reasons which were very well known."{{sfnp|Casey|2014}}

=== Earl Doherty ===
Canadian writer [[Earl Doherty]] (born 1941) was introduced to the Christ myth theme by a lecture by Wells in the 1970s.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}}{{efn-lr|His subsequential study of the topic was published as ''The Jesus Puzzle'' in a series of articles in the Humanist (1995–1996){{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}} and as a book (1999), and republished as ''Jesus: Neither God nor Man – The Case for a Mythical Jesus'' (2009).}} Doherty follows the lead of Wells, but disagrees on the historicity of Jesus, arguing that "everything in Paul points to a belief in an entirely divine Son who "lived" and acted in the spiritual realm, in the same mythical setting in which all the other savior deities of the day were seen to operate".{{sfnp|Doherty|1995a|ps=none}} According to Doherty, Paul's Christ originated as a myth derived from [[middle Platonism]] with some influence from [[Merkabah mysticism|Jewish mysticism]] and belief in a historical Jesus emerged only among Christian communities in the 2nd century.{{sfnp|Doherty|2009|p=vii–viii}}

Paul and other writers of the earliest existing proto-Christian documents did not believe in Jesus as a person who was incarnated on Earth in a historical setting, rather they believed in Jesus as a heavenly being who suffered his sacrificial death in the lower spheres of heaven, where he was crucified by demons and then was subsequently resurrected by God. This mythological Jesus was not based on a historical Jesus, but rather on an [[exegesis]] of the Old Testament in the context of Jewish-Hellenistic religious syncretism and what the early authors believed to be mystical visions of a risen Jesus.{{sfnp|Doherty|2009}}

Doherty agrees with Bauckham that the earliest Christology was already a "high Christology," that is, Jesus was an incarnation of the pre-existent Christ, but deems it "hardly credible" that such a belief could develop in such a short time among Jews.<ref>Doherty (2009). Jesus: Neither God Nor Man – The Case for a Mythical Jesus. Ottawa: Age of Reason Publications. p. 716, n. 12. {{ISBN|978-0-9689259-2-8}}</ref> Therefore, Doherty concludes that Christianity started  with the myth of this incarnated Christ, who was subsequently historicised.

According to Doherty, the nucleus of this historicised Jesus of the Gospels can be found in the Jesus-movement which wrote the Q source.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}} According to Doherty, the Q-authors may have regarded themselves as "spokespersons for the Wisdom of God", with Jesus being the embodiment of this Wisdom,{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Doherty|1997}} who was added in the latest phase of the development of Q.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}} Q then started to take the form of a "foundation document", in response to a concurring sect who saw John the Baptist as its founder.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}} Eventually, Q's Jesus and Paul's Christ were combined in the Gospel of Mark by a predominantly gentile community.{{sfnp|Doherty|1995d|ps=none}} In time, the gospel-narrative of this embodiment of Wisdom became interpreted as the literal history of the life of Jesus.{{sfnp|Doherty|1997}}

New Testament scholar Bart Ehrman quotes Doherty from ''The Jesus Puzzle'' as maintaining that it was Paul's view that Jesus' death took place in the spiritual not the earthly realm,<ref name="Bart D. Ehrman 2">{{cite book |last1=Ehrman|first1=Bart D.|title=Did Jesus Exist?: The Historical Argument for Jesus of Nazareth|date=2012|publisher=Harper One|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-20899-46}}</ref>{{rp|258}} but according to Ehrman, not only is there "no evidence to support Doherty's assertion of what Paul's view of Jesus was", but there are also "a host of reasons for calling Doherty's view into serious question."<ref name="Bart D. Ehrman 2"/>{{rp|254,258}}

In a book criticizing the Christ myth theory, New Testament scholar [[Maurice Casey]] describes Doherty as "perhaps the most influential of all the mythicists",{{sfnp|Casey|2014|p=2}} but one who is unable to understand the ancient texts he uses in his arguments.{{sfnp|Casey|2014|p=16}}

=== Robert M. Price ===
[[File:Robert M. Price 1.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|alt=Robert Price at a microphone|American New Testament scholar [[Robert M. Price]]]]
American New Testament scholar and former [[Baptist]] pastor Robert M. Price (born 1954) was a fellow of the [[Jesus Seminar]], a group of writers and scholars who study the historicity of Jesus and who argue that the Christian image of Christ is a theological construct into which traces of Jesus of Nazareth have been woven.<ref>Van Biema, David; Ostling, Richard N.; and Towle, Lisa H. [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,984367-1,00.html "The Gospel Truth?"]. ''Time'' magazine. April 8, 1996.</ref> He was also a member of the [[Jesus Project]].

Price questioned the historicity of Jesus in a series of books, including ''Deconstructing Jesus'' (2000), ''The Incredible Shrinking Son of Man'' (2003), ''Jesus Is Dead'' (2007) and ''The Christ-Myth Theory and Its Problems'' (2011), as well as in contributions to ''The Historical Jesus: Five Views'' (2009), in which he acknowledges that he stands against the majority view of scholars, but cautions against attempting to settle the issue by appeal to the majority.{{sfnp|Price|2009|pp=61ff}} Price notes that "consensus is no criterion" for the historicity of Jesus.{{refn|group=q|name="Price.2009.61"}}

In ''Deconstructing Jesus'', Price points out that "the Jesus Christ of the New Testament is a composite figure", out of which a broad variety of historical Jesuses can be reconstructed, any one of which may have been the real Jesus, but not all of them together.{{sfnp|Price|2000|pp=15–16}} According to Price, various Jesus images flowed together at the origin of Christianity, some of them possibly based on myth, some of them possibly based on "a historical Jesus the Nazorean".{{sfnp|Price|2000|p=86}} Price admits uncertainty in this regard, writing in conclusion: "There may have been a real figure there, but there is simply no longer any way of being sure".{{sfnp|Price|2000|p=261}}{{refn|group=q|name="Price.Quest"}}

According to Price, the accounts of Jesus are derived from Jewish writings,{{Refn|name="Price.scripture"}} which show Greek influences and similarities with Pagan saviour deities. Christianity is a historicized synthesis of mainly Egyptian, Jewish, and Greek mythologies.{{refn|1={{harvp|Price|2009|pp=55ff}}
* Also see Robert M. Price's review of ''Christ in Egypt: The Horus-Jesus Connection''.<ref name="Christ in Egypt"/>}} Price maintains that there are three key points for the traditional Christ myth theory:<ref>{{harvp|Price|2009}}
# There is no mention of a miracle working Jesus in secular sources. (p. 62)
# The epistles, which were written before the gospels, do not evidence a recent historical Jesus. (p. 63)
# The Jesus story shows strong parallels to other Mediterranean religions that were also based on gods that died and rose again. (p. 75)</ref>
* There is no mention of a miracle-working Jesus in secular sources.
* The epistles, written earlier than the gospels, provide no evidence of a recent historical Jesus and all that can be taken from the epistles, Price argues, is that a Jesus Christ, son of God, lived in a heavenly realm, there died as a sacrifice for human sin, was raised by God and enthroned in heaven.
* The Jesus narrative is paralleled in Middle Eastern myths about dying and rising gods. Price names [[Baʿal#Deities called Baʿal and Baʿalath|Baal]], [[Osiris]], [[Attis]], [[Adonis]] and [[Tammuz (deity)|Dumuzi/Tammuz]] as examples, all of which, he writes, survived into the Hellenistic and Roman periods and thereby influenced early Christianity. Price alleges that Christian apologists have tried to minimize these parallels.<ref name=Price62>{{harvp|Price|2009}}{{bulleted list|See p. 55 for his argument that it is quite likely Jesus did not exist. |See pp. 62–64, 75 for the three pillars}}</ref><ref name="BeilbyEddy2010">{{cite book|author=Darrell L. Bock |editor=James K. Beilby |editor2=Paul Rhodes Eddy |title=The Historical Jesus: Five Views |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O33P7xrFnLQC&pg=PA99 |date=2010|publisher=InterVarsity Press|isbn=978-0-8308-7853-6|pages=99–103|chapter=Response to Robert M. Price}}</ref>

Citing accounts that have Jesus being crucified under [[Alexander Jannaeus]] (83 BC) or in his 50s by [[Herod Agrippa I]] under the rule of [[Claudius]] (AD 41–54). Price argues that these "varying dates are the residue of various attempts to anchor an originally mythic or legendary Jesus in more or less recent history".{{sfnp|Price|2009|pp=80–81}}

=== Thomas L. Thompson ===
[[Thomas L. Thompson]] (born 1939), Professor emeritus of theology at the [[University of Copenhagen]], is a leading [[Biblical minimalism|biblical minimalist]] of the Old Testament.{{refn|group=q|name="Casey2014"}} According to Thompson, the accounts of Jesus are derived from Jewish writings.{{sfnp|Thompson|2012}} In his 2007 book ''The Messiah Myth: The Near Eastern Roots of Jesus and David'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Messiah Myth |publisher= Penguin Books Australia|url=https://penguin.com.au/books/the-messiah-myth-9780712668439|website=penguin.com.au|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref> Thompson argues that the biblical accounts of both King David and Jesus of Nazareth are mythical in nature and based on Mesopotamian, Egyptian, Babylonian and Greek and Roman literature. For example, he argues that the resurrection of Jesus is taken directly from the story of the dying and rising god, [[Dionysus]].{{refn|group=q|name="Thompson.Messiah.Myth"}}{{refn|group=q|name="Ehrman.2012.p11_15"}} However, Thompson does not draw a final conclusion on the historicity or ahistoricity of Jesus, but argued that any historical person would be very different from the Christ (or Messiah) identified in the Gospel of Mark.{{refn|group=q|name="Thompson.2009.p3"}}

Thompson coedited the contributions from a diverse range of scholars in the 2012 book ''Is This Not the Carpenter?: The Question of the Historicity of the Figure of Jesus''.{{sfnp|Thompson|Verenna|2012|ps=none}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Is This Not the Carpenter? (Contents) |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/is-this-not-the-carpenter/23611D6CA766967BBE1A1A1AB66684FA |website=Cambridge Core |publisher=Cambridge University Press |accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref> Writing in the introduction, "The essays collected in this volume have a modest purpose. Neither establishing the historicity of a historical Jesus nor possessing an adequate warrant for dismissing it, our purpose is to clarify our engagement with critical historical and exegetical methods."{{sfnp|Thompson|Verenna|2012|loc=Introduction}}

In a 2012 online article, Thompson defended his qualifications to address New Testament issues and he rejected the label of "mythicist" and reiterated his position that the issue of Jesus' existence cannot be determined one way or the other. Thompson contends that the present state of New Testament scholarship viz. Bart Ehrman "is such that an established scholar should present his Life of Jesus, without considering whether this figure, in fact, lived as a historical person" and that such assumptions "reflect a serious problem regarding the historical quality of scholarship in biblical studies".{{sfnp|Thompson|2012}}

=== Thomas L. Brodie ===
In 2012, the Irish Dominican priest and theologian [[Thomas L. Brodie]] (born 1943), holding a PhD from the [[Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas]] in [[Rome]] and a co-founder and former director of the [[Dominican Biblical Institute]] in [[Limerick]], published ''Beyond the Quest for the Historical Jesus: Memoir of a Discovery''. In this book, Brodie, who previously had published academic works on the Hebrew prophets, argued that the Gospels are essentially a rewriting of the stories of Elijah and Elisha when viewed as a unified account in the [[Books of Kings]]. This view lead Brodie to the conclusion that Jesus is mythical.<ref name="brodie2012">{{cite book |last=Brodie|first=Thomas L.|year=2012|title=Beyond the Quest for the Historical Jesus: Memoir of a Discovery|publisher=Sheffield Phoenix Press|isbn=978-1-9075-3458-4|page=}}</ref> Brodie's argument builds on his previous work, in which he stated that rather than being separate and fragmented, the stories of Elijah and Elisha are united and that 1 Kings 16:29–2 Kings 13:25 is a natural extension of 1 Kings 17–2 Kings 8 which have a coherence not generally observed by other biblical scholars.<ref name=brodie2000>{{cite book|last=Brodie|first=Thomas L.|year=2000|title=The crucial bridge: the Elijah-Elisha narrative as an interpretive synthesis of Genesis-Kings and a literary model of the Gospels|location=Collegeville, MN|publisher=Liturgical Press|isbn=9780814659427|pages=1–3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ittqkiibm0C&pg=PA1}}</ref> Brodie then views the Elijah–Elisha story as the underlying model for the gospel narratives.<ref name="brodie2000" />

In response to Brodie's publication of his view that Jesus was mythical, the Dominican order banned him from writing and lecturing, although he was allowed to stay on as a brother of the Irish Province, which continued to care for him.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Beyond the Quest for the Historical Jesus – Official Dominican Response to a Controversial Book|journal=Doctrine and Life|publisher=Dominican Publications|date=May–June 2014}}</ref> "There is an unjustifiable jump between methodology and conclusion" in Brodie's book—according to Gerard Norton—and "are not soundly based on scholarship". According to Norton, they are "a memoir of a series of significant moments or events" in Brodie's life that reinforced "his core conviction" that neither Jesus nor Paul of Tarsus were historical.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barry|first=Cathal|date=April 10, 2014|title=Cleric faces dismissal over claim that Jesus Christ 'did not exist'{{thinsp}} |website= irishcatholic.ie |location=Dublin |publisher=Irish Catholic |url= http://www.irishcatholic.ie/article/cleric-faces-dismissal-over-claim-jesus-christ-did-not-exist |dead-url=no |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160412024546/http://www.irishcatholic.ie/article/cleric-faces-dismissal-over-claim-jesus-christ-did-not-exist |archive-date= April 12, 2016 |access-date= April 12, 2016}}</ref>

=== Richard Carrier ===
[[File:RichardCarrierSM.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|[[Richard Carrier]]]]
American independent scholar{{sfnp|Gullotta|2017}} Richard Carrier (born 1969) reviewed Doherty's work on the origination of Jesus{{sfnp|Carrier|2002}} and eventually concluded that the evidence actually favored the core Doherty thesis.{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier 2014 p614–616"}} According to Carrier, following Couchoud{{refn|group=q|name="Couchoud1926_p23"}} and Doherty, Christianity started with the belief in a new deity called Jesus,{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier.OHJ"}} "a spiritual, mythical figure."{{refn|group=q|name="Doherty.2009.mythical.figure"}} According to Carrier, this new deity was fleshed out in the Gospels, which added a narrative framework and [[Cynicism (philosophy)|Cynic]]-like teachings, and eventually came to be perceived as a historical biography.{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier.OHJ"}} According to Carrier, for such a person to be considered "the historical Jesus in any pertinent sense", such a person must comply with his definition of a minimal historical Jesus.{{refn|group=q|name="Carrier.2014.34"}}

According to Carrier, many studies by mainstream scholars have shown that the current consensus of a historical Jesus is based on invalid methods.{{sfnp|Carrier|2014|loc=Chapter 2}}{{efn-lr|name=studies|For example:{{bulleted list |Chris Keith and Anthony LeDonne (eds.), ''Jesus, History and the Demise of Authenticity'' (New York: T. & T. Clark, 2012) |Dale Allison, 'The Historians' Jesus and the Church', in ''Seeking the Identity of Jesus: A Pilgrimage'' (ed. Beverly Roberts Gaventa and Richard Hays; Grand Rapids, Ml: William B. Eerdmans, 2008), pp. 79–95 |Hector Avalos, ''The End of Biblical Studies'' (Amherst. NY: Prometheus Books, 2007), pp. 185–217 |Gerd Theissen and Dagmar Winter, ''The Quest for the Plausible Jesus: The Question of Criteria'' (Louisville. KY: John Knox Press, 2002) |Stanley Porter, ''The Criteria for Authenticity in Historical-Jesus Research: Previous Discussion and New Proposals'' (Sheffield: Sheffield Academic Press, 2000)}}}} Carrier also claims that [[historical method]]ologies often use [[Fallacy|fallacious reasoning]]{{refn|group=q|name="HistoryasaScience"}} and that they must be drastically revised.{{refn|group=q|name="Joseph.2015.paradigm"}}

Carrier argues in his book ''On the Historicity of Jesus: Why We Might Have Reason for Doubt'' that there is insufficient [[Bayesian probability]], that is evidence, to believe in the existence of Jesus. Furthermore, Carrier argues that the Jesus figure was probably originally known only through private revelations and hidden messages in scripture which were then crafted into a historical figure to communicate the claims of the gospels allegorically. These allegories then started to be believed as fact during the struggle for control of the Christian churches of the first century. He argues that the probability of Jesus' existence is somewhere in the range from 1/3 to 1/12000 depending on the estimates used for the computation.{{sfnp|Carrier|2014}}

His methodology was reviewed by Aviezer Tucker, a prior advocate of using [[Bayesian inference|Bayesian techniques]] in history. Tucker expressed some sympathy for Carrier's view of the Gospels, stating: "The problem with the Synoptic Gospels as evidence for a historical Jesus from a Bayesian perspective is that the evidence that coheres does not seem to be independent, whereas the evidence that is independent does not seem to cohere". However, Tucker argued that historians have been able to use theories about the transmission and preservation of information to identify reliable parts of the Gospels. He said that "Carrier is too dismissive of such methods because he is focused on hypotheses about the historical Jesus rather than on the best explanations of the evidence".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tucker|first1=Aviezer|title=The Reverend Bayes vs Jesus Christ|journal=History and Theory |date=February 2016 |volume=55:1 |pages=129–140 |doi= 10.1111/hith.10791}}</ref>

In the peer-reviewed scholarly [[Journal for the Study of the Historical Jesus]] Daniel N. Gullotta, reviewing Carrier's ''On the Historicity of Jesus: Why We Might Have Reason for Doubt'', says he finds Carrier's arguments "problematic and unpersuasive", his use of Bayesian probabilities "unnecessarily complex" and criticizes Carrier's "lack of evidence, strained readings and troublesome assumptions."  Gullotta also states that there is absolutely no evidence whatsoever, either documentary or archaeological, that there was a period when Christians believed that Jesus only existed in heaven rather than living as a human being on earth, which is Carrier's "foundational" thesis.{{sfnp|Gullotta|2017}}

=== Other modern proponents ===
[[File:John Marco Allegro.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|British academic [[John M. Allegro]]]]
In his books ''[[The Sacred Mushroom and the Cross]]'' (1970) and ''[[The Dead Sea Scrolls and the Christian Myth]]'' (1979), the British archaeologist and philologist [[John M. Allegro]] advanced the theory that stories of early Christianity originated in a [[shamanism|shamanistic]] [[Essene]] clandestine cult centered around the use of [[Psilocybin mushroom|hallucinogenic mushrooms]].<ref>John Allegro, ''The Sacred Mushroom and the Cross'' 1970 {{ISBN|978-0-9825562-7-6}}</ref><ref>John Allegro ''The Dead Sea Scrolls and the Christian Myth'' 1979 {{ISBN|978-0-879-75757-1}}</ref><ref name=Meaning323/><ref name=Taylor305>''The Essenes, the Scrolls, and the Dead Sea'' by Joan E. Taylor (2012) {{ISBN|019955448X}} Oxford University Press p. 305</ref> He also argued that the story of Jesus was based on the crucifixion of the [[Teacher of Righteousness]] in the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]].{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|p=77}}<ref>Hall, Mark. "Foreword," in Allegro, John M. ''The Dead Sea Scrolls & the Christian Myth''. Prometheus 1992, first published 1979, p. ix.</ref> Allegro's theory was criticised sharply by Welsh historian [[Philip Jenkins]], who wrote that Allegro relied on texts that did not exist in quite the form he was citing them.<ref>Jenkins, Philip. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Wv6x5kTHGvsC&pg=PA180 ''Hidden Gospels'']. Oxford University Press, 2002, p. 180.</ref> Based on this and many other negative reactions to the book, Allegro's publisher later apologized for issuing the book and Allegro was forced to resign his academic post.<ref name=Meaning323>''The Meaning of the Dead Sea Scrolls'' by Peter Flint and James VanderKam (2005) {{ISBN|056708468X}} T&T Clark pages 323–325</ref><ref name=MidE82>''A History of the Middle East'' by Saul S. Friedman (2006) {{ISBN|0786423560}} p. 82</ref>

Using a reverse-translation mechanism, [[Bernard Dubourg]]'s two-volume work in French on the New Testament (1987/1989) argued that the Greek text was originally composed in Hebrew instead of Greek, according to the traditional procedures of midrash. Following Paul Vulliaud, Dubourg emphasized the importance of gematria in showing the coherence of his back-translated text. He concludes that Paul is as mythical as Jesus.

[[Alvar Ellegård]], in ''The Myth of Jesus'' (1992), and ''Jesus: One Hundred Years Before Christ. A Study in Creative Mythology'' (1999), argued that Jesus lived 100 years before the accepted dates, and was a teacher of the Essenes. According to Ellegård, Paul was connected with the Essenes, and had a vision of this Jesus.

Timothy Freke and [[Peter Gandy (author)|Peter Gandy]], in their 1999 publication ''The Jesus Mysteries: Was the "Original Jesus" a Pagan God?'' propose that Jesus did not literally exist as an historically identifiable individual, but was instead a [[Syncretism|syncretic]] re-interpretation of the fundamental pagan "godman" by the [[Gnostic]]s, who were the original sect of Christianity. The book has been negatively received by scholars, and also by Christ mythicists.<ref name="auto">{{cite web |url=http://your.sydneyanglicans.net/culture/thinking/387a/ |title=The Jesus Mysteries – a critique |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921085911/http://your.sydneyanglicans.net/culture/thinking/387a/ |archive-date=September 21, 2007 }}</ref><ref name="auto"/><ref>Bart Ehrman, interview with David V. Barrett, "The Gospel According to Bart", ''Fortean Times'' (221), 2007</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://freethoughtblogs.com/carrier/archives/1026 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117094139/http://freethoughtblogs.com/carrier/archives/1026 |archivedate=January 17, 2016  }}</ref>

[[File:Photo of Tom Harpur by Hugh Wesley.jpg|right|thumb|upright=0.6|Canadian author [[Tom Harpur]] (photo by Hugh Wesley)]]
Influenced by Massey and Higgins, [[Alvin Boyd Kuhn]] (1880–1963) argued an Egyptian etymology to the Bible that the gospels were symbolic rather than historic and that church leaders started to misinterpret the New Testament in the third century.<ref>[http://members.tripod.com/~pc93/abbskcth.htm Alvin Boyd Kuhn, Ph.D. A Biographical Sketch of his life and work], by Richard Alvin Sattelberg, B.A., M.S.., 2005</ref> Author and ordained priest [[Tom Harpur]] dedicated his 2004 book ''[[The Pagan Christ]]'' to Kuhn, suggesting that Kuhn has not received the attention he deserves since many of his works were self-published.{{sfnp|Harpur|2004}} Building on Kuhn's work, Harpur listed similarities among the stories of Jesus, Horus, Mithras, Buddha and others. According to Harpur, in the second or third centuries the early church created the fictional impression of a literal and historic Jesus and then used forgery and violence to cover up the evidence.{{sfnp|Harpur|2004}} Harpur's book received a great deal of [[The Pagan Christ#Criticism and responses|criticism]], including a response book, ''Unmasking the Pagan Christ: An Evangelical Response to the Cosmic Christ Idea''.<ref>{{Cite book|ref=harv |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NwPvu3r6ZzUC |title=Unmasking the Pagan Christ: An Evangelical Response to the Cosmic Christ Idea |last=Porter |first=Stanley E. |last2=Bedard |first2=Stephen J. |date=2006 |publisher=Clements Publishing Group |isbn=978-1-8946-6771-5}}</ref> Fellow mythicist Robert M. Price also wrote a negative review, saying that he did not agree that the Egyptian parallels were as forceful as Harpur thought.<ref name="Price.Harpur">{{cite web|author1=Robert M. Price|authorlink1=Robert M. Price|title=Review – Tom Harpur, The Pagan Christ: Recovering the Lost Light reviewed by Robert M. Price |url=http://www.robertmprice.mindvendor.com/reviews/harpur_pagan_christ.htm |website=www.robertmprice.mindvendor.com |accessdate=September 3, 2016|date=2009}}</ref> In 2007, Harpur published a sequel, ''Water Into Wine''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5dZsAAAAQBAJ|title=Water Into Wine: An Empowering Vision of the Gospels|last=Harpur|first=Tom|date=2008|publisher=Dundurn.com|isbn=9780887628276|language=en}}</ref>

David Fitzgerald has self-published several works in defense of the Christ myth theory, including  ''Nailed: 10 Christian Myths That Show Jesus Never Existed At All'' (2010), and ''Jesus: Mything in Action'', Vols. I–III (2017).

In his 2017 book ''Décadence'', French writer and philosopher [[Michel Onfray]] argued for the Christ myth theory and based his hypothesis on the fact that—other than in the New Testament—Jesus is barely mentioned in accounts of the period.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Waugh |first1=Rob |title=‘Jesus never actually existed at all,’ controversial French author argues |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/04/12/jesus-never-actually-existed-at-all-controversial-french-author-argues-6571007/ |website=Metro |date=April 12, 2017}}</ref>

The Christ myth theory enjoyed brief popularity in the [[Soviet Union]], where it was supported by [[Sergey Kovalev (historian)|Sergey Kovalev]], [[Alexander Kazhdan]], [[Abram Ranovich]], [[Nikolai Rumyantsev (historian)|Nikolai Rumyantsev]] and [[Robert Vipper]].<ref name="Andreev">{{cite web | url =http://pstgu.ru/download/1430825026.5_andreev_73-88.pdf |title=Дискуссия об историчности Иисуса Христа в советском религиоведении|author=А. В. Андреев|work=Вестник ПСТГУ|language=Russian| date=2015| accessdate =June 12, 2015}}</ref> However, several scholars, including Kazhdan, later retracted their views about mythical Jesus and by the end of the 1980s [[Iosif Kryvelev]] remained as virtually the only proponent of Christ myth theory in Soviet academia.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.gumer.info/bogoslov_Buks/bogoslov/Golol/03.php|title=Богословие и национальный вопрос|author=Гололоб Г.|publisher=Библиотека Гумер| language=Russian| accessdate =June 12, 2015}}</ref>

==Reception==

=== Popular reception ===
In a 2015 poll conducted by the [[Church of England]], 40% of respondents indicated that they did not believe Jesus was a real person.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-34686993 |title=Jesus 'not a real person' many believe |date=October 31, 2015 |website=BBC |access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref>

Ehrman notes that "the mythicists have become loud, and thanks to the Internet they've attracted more attention".<ref name="Ehrman.2015.Debate" /> Within a few years of the inception of the [[History of the World Wide Web|World Wide Web]] (c. 1990),  mythicists such as Earl Doherty began to present their argument to a larger public via the internet.{{refn|group=q|name="Doherty.1997.Mack"}} Doherty created the website ''The Jesus Puzzle'' in 1996,<ref name="Doherty.2011.Godfrey"/> while the organization [[Internet Infidels]] has featured the works of mythicists on their website<ref name="Internet.Infidels.Historicity" /> and mythicism has been mentioned on several popular news sites.{{refn|group=q|name="Gullotta.2017.311"}}

According to Derek Murphy, the documentaries ''[[The God Who Wasn't There]]'' (2005) and ''[[Zeitgeist (film series)#Zeitgeist: The Movie|Zeitgeist]]'' (2007) raised interest for the Christ myth theory with a larger audience and gave the topic a large coverage on the Internet.{{sfnp|Murphy|2011|p=65}} Daniel Gullotta notes the relationship between the organization "Atheists United" and Carrier's work related to Mythicism, which has increased "the attention of the public".{{refn|group=q|name="Gullotta.2015"}}

According to Ehrman, mythicism has a growing appeal "because these deniers of Jesus are at the same time denouncers of religion".<ref name="Ehrman_Huffington"/>{{refn|group=q|name="Ehrman.2012.337"}} According to Casey, mythicism has a growing appeal because of an aversion toward Christian fundamentalism among American atheists.{{sfnp|Casey|2014}}

=== Scholarly reception ===
In modern scholarship, the Christ myth theory is a [[fringe theory]] and finds virtually no support from scholars.{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2003|pp=658, 660}}{{sfnp|Fox|2005|p=48}}{{sfnp|Burridge|Gould|2004|p=34}}<ref name="Ehrman Blog">{{cite web|last=Ehrman|first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman|title=Fuller Reply to Richard Carrier|url=https://ehrmanblog.org/fuller-reply-to-richard-carrier/|website=The Bart Ehrman Blog|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=April 25, 2012}}</ref>{{refn|group=q|name="Grantmajority"}}

==== Lack of support for mythicism ====
According to New Testament scholar Bart D. Ehrman, most people who study the historical period of Jesus believe that he did exist and do not write in support of the Christ myth theory.{{sfnp|Ehrman|2012|p=2}}

[[Maurice Casey]], [[theologian]] and scholar of New Testament and early Christianity, stated that the belief among professors that Jesus existed is generally completely certain. According to Casey, the view that Jesus did not exist is "the view of extremists", "demonstrably false" and "professional scholars generally regard it as having been settled in serious scholarship long ago".<ref>Casey, Maurice, ''Jesus of Nazareth: An Independent Historian's Account of His Life and Teaching'' ([[T&T Clark]], 2010), pp. 33, 104, 499.</ref>

In his 1977 book ''Jesus: An Historian's Review of the Gospels'', classical historian and popular author [[Michael Grant (author)|Michael Grant]] concluded that "modern critical methods fail to support the Christ-myth theory".<ref name="Grant1977">Michael Grant (1977), ''Jesus: An Historian's Review of the Gospels''. Charles Scribner's Sons, p. 200.</ref> In support of this, Grant quoted [[Roderic Dunkerley]]'s 1957 opinion that the Christ myth theory has "again and again been answered and annihilated by first-rank scholars".<ref>[[Roderic Dunkerley|Dunkerley, Roderic]], ''Beyond the Gospels'' (Penguin Books, 1957) p. 12.</ref> At the same time, he also quoted Otto Betz's 1968 opinion that in recent years "no serious scholar has ventured to postulate the non-historicity of Jesus—or at any rate very few, and they have not succeeded in disposing of the much stronger, indeed very abundant, evidence to the contrary".<ref>Betz, Otto, What Do We Know About Jesus? (SCM-Canterbury Press, 1968) p. 9.</ref> In the same book, he also wrote: {{quote|If we apply to the New Testament, as we should, the same sort of criteria as we should apply to other ancient writings containing historical material, we can no more reject Jesus' existence than we can reject the existence of a mass of pagan personages whose reality as historical figures is never questioned.{{sfnp|Grant19|1995}}}}

Graeme Clarke, Emeritus Professor of Classical Ancient History and Archaeology at [[Australian National University]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Academy Fellows |url=http://www.humanities.org.au/Fellowship/FindFellows/tabid/123/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1092/Clarke-Graeme.aspx |publisher=Australian Academy of the Humanities|accessdate=June 11, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527092213/http://www.humanities.org.au/Fellowship/FindFellows/tabid/123/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1092/Clarke-Graeme.aspx|archivedate=May 27, 2014}}</ref> has stated: "Frankly, I know of no ancient historian or biblical historian who would have a twinge of doubt about the existence of a Jesus Christ—the documentary evidence is simply overwhelming".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dickson|first1=John|title=Facts and friction of Easter|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/news/national/facts-and-friction-of-easter/2008/03/21/1205602592557.html?page=3|accessdate=June 11, 2015|publisher=Brisbane Times|date=March 21, 2008}}</ref>

R. Joseph Hoffmann, who had created the [[Jesus Project]], which included both mythicists and historicists to investigate the historicity of Jesus, wrote that an adherent to the Christ myth theory asked to set up a separate section of the project for those committed to the theory. Hoffmann felt that to be committed to mythicism signaled a lack of necessary skepticism and he noted that most members of the project did not reach the mythicist conclusion.<ref name=Hoffmann>Hoffmann, R. Joseph. [http://www.bibleinterp.com/opeds/hoffman1044.shtml "Threnody: Rethinking the Thinking behind The Jesus Project"], bibleinterp.com, October 2009, accessed August 6, 2010.</ref>

==== Questioning the competence of proponents ====
Critics of the Christ myth theory question the competence of its supporters.{{refn|group=q|name="Casey2014"}} According to Ehrman: {{quote|Few of these mythicists are actually scholars trained in ancient history, religion, biblical studies or any cognate field, let alone in the ancient languages generally thought to matter for those who want to say something with any degree of authority about a Jewish teacher who (allegedly) lived in first-century Palestine.<ref name="Ehrman_Huffington"/>}}

In a response, Thompson questioned the polemical nature of this qualification, pointing at his own academic standing and expertise. According to Thompson, Ehrman "has attributed to my book arguments and principles which I had never presented, certainly not that Jesus had never existed". Thompson questions Ehrman's qualifications in regard to Old Testamentical writings and research, as well as his competence to recognize the problems involved in "reiterated narrative" and "the historicity of a literary figure", stating that Ehrman had "thoroughly [...] misunderstood [...] the very issue of the historicity of the New Testament figure of Jesus".{{sfnp|Thompson|2012}}

Maurice Casey has criticized the mythicists, pointing out their complete ignorance of how modern critical scholarship actually works. He also criticizes mythicists for their frequent assumption that all modern scholars of religion are Protestant fundamentalists of the American variety, insisting that this assumption is not only totally inaccurate, but also exemplary of the mythicists' misconceptions about the ideas and attitudes of mainstream scholars.{{sfnp|Casey|2014|pp=1–41}}

Questioning the mainstream view appears to have consequences for one's job perspectives.{{efn-lr|See Thomas Verenna, [https://tomverenna.wordpress.com/2014/08/19/goodbye-for-now/ ''Goodbye for now?'']}} According to Casey, Thompson's early work, which "successfully refuted the attempts of Albright and others to defend the historicity of the most ancient parts of biblical literature history", has "negatively affected his future job prospects".{{refn|group=q|name="Casey2014"}} Ehrman also notes that mythicist views would prevent one from getting employment in a religious studies department: {{quote|These views are so extreme and so unconvincing to 99.99 percent of the real experts that anyone holding them is as likely to get a teaching job in an established department of religion as a six-day creationist is likely to land on in a bona fide department of biology.<ref name="Ehrman_Huffington"/>}}

====Opponents====
Few scholars have bothered to criticise Christ myth theories. Robert Van Voorst has written "Contemporary New Testament scholars have typically viewed (Christ myth) arguments as so weak or bizarre that they relegate them to footnotes, or often ignore them completely...The theory of Jesus' nonexistence is now effectively dead as a scholarly question."{{sfnp|Van Voorst|2000|p=6}} [[Paul L. Maier]], former Professor of Ancient History at Western Michigan University and current  professor emeritus in the Department of History there has stated "Anyone who uses the argument that Jesus never existed is simply flaunting his ignorance."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grace |first1=John Patrick |title=Questioning Jesus' existence is sheer madness |url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/opinion/john-patrick-grace-questioning-jesus-existence-is-sheer-madness/article_2223a091-477e-5f55-a8a8-ee50b372fe9e.html |accessdate=August 7, 2018 |publisher=The Herald-Dispatch |date=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Among notable scholars who have directly addressed the Christ myth are Bart Ehrman, Maurice Casey and Philip Jenkins.

=====Bart Ehrman=====
{{Main|Did Jesus Exist? (Ehrman)}}

In this book, [[Bart Ehrman]] surveys the arguments "mythicists" have made against the existence of Jesus since the idea was first mooted at the end of the 18th century. To the objection that there are no contemporary Roman records of Jesus' existence, Ehrman points out that such records exist for almost no one and there are mentions of Christ in several Roman works of history from only decades after the [[death of Jesus]].<ref name=Ehrman>{{cite book|last=Ehrman|first=Bart D,|title=Did Jesus Exist?: The Historical Argument for Jesus of Nazareth|date=2012|publisher=HarperOne|isbn=978-0062206442}}</ref><ref name=Shimron>{{cite news|last=Shimron|first=Yonat|title=In 'Did Jesus Exist?' Bart Ehrman's Portrayal Of Jesus Is Surprisingly Sympathetic|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/03/did-jesus-exist-bart-ehrman_n_1400465.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=May 26, 2014|date=April 3, 2012}}</ref> The author states that the authentic letters of the apostle [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] in the New Testament were likely written within a few years of Jesus' death and that Paul likely personally knew [[James the Just|James]], the brother of Jesus.<ref name="Ehrman_Huffington"/> Although the [[gospel]] accounts of Jesus' life may be biased and unreliable in many respects, Ehrman writes, they and the sources behind them which scholars have discerned still contain some accurate historical information.<ref name=Ehrman /><ref name=Shimron /> So many independent attestations of Jesus' existence, Ehrman says, are actually "astounding for an ancient figure of any kind".<ref name="Ehrman_Huffington"/> Ehrman dismisses the idea that the story of Jesus is an invention based on [[Paganism|pagan myths]] of dying-and-rising gods, maintaining that the early Christians were primarily influenced by [[Judaism|Jewish ideas]], not Greek or Roman ones,<ref name=Ehrman /><ref name="Ehrman_Huffington"/> and repeatedly insisting that the idea that there was never such a person as Jesus is not seriously considered by historians or experts in the field at all.<ref name=Ehrman />

=====Maurice Casey=====
In ''Jesus: Evidence and Argument or Mythicist Myths?'' (2014), scholar of New Testament and early Christianity [[Maurice Casey]] treats the historical method, the reliability of the Gospels, the argument from silence from both the Gospels and the Pauline epistles, and the similarities with other religions of the time.{{sfnp|Casey|2014}} According to Casey, many mythicists seem to object to fundamentalist perceptions of Christianity, while ignoring or being ignorant of liberal forms of Christianity.{{sfnp|Casey|2014}}

=====Philip Jenkins=====
[[Philip Jenkins]], Distinguished Professor of History at [[Baylor University]], has written "What you can’t do, though, without venturing into the far swamps of extreme crankery, is to argue that Jesus never existed. The “Christ-Myth Hypothesis” is not scholarship, and is not taken seriously in respectable academic debate. The grounds advanced for the “hypothesis” are worthless. The authors proposing such opinions might be competent, decent, honest individuals, but the views they present are demonstrably wrong....Jesus is better documented and recorded than pretty much any non-elite figure of antiquity."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jenkins|first1=Phillip|title=The Myth of the Mythical Jesus|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/anxiousbench/2016/04/the-myth-of-the-mythical-jesus/#IGPQmrQ3pSPteW5M.99|website=patheos.com|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref>

===Traditional and Evangelical Christianity===
Alexander Lucie-Smith, Catholic priest and doctor of moral theology, states that "People who think Jesus didn’t exist are seriously confused," but also notes that "the Church needs to reflect on its failure. If 40 per cent believe in the Jesus myth, this is a sign that the Church has failed to communicate with the general public."<ref name=Lucie-Smith>Fr Alexander Lucie-Smith, [http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/commentandblogs/2015/11/02/people-who-think-jesus-didnt-exist-are-seriously-confused/ ''People who think Jesus didn’t exist are seriously confused''], Catholic Herald</ref>

[[Stanley E. Porter]], president and dean of [[McMaster Divinity College]] in Hamilton, and Stephen J. Bedard, a Baptist minister and graduate of McMaster Divinity, respond to [[The Pagan Christ|Harpur's ideas]] from an evangelical standpoint in ''Unmasking the Pagan Christ: An Evangelical Response to the Cosmic Christ Idea'', challenging the key ideas lying at the foundation of Harpur's thesis. Porter and Bedard conclude that there is sufficient evidence for the historicity of Jesus and assert that Harpur is motivated to promote "universalistic spirituality".{{sfnp|Porter|Bedard|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=NwPvu3r6ZzUC&pg=PA69#v=onepage&q&f=false 69]}}{{efn-lr|See also Stephen J. Bedard, [http://www.stephenjbedard.com/jesus-myth/ ''Jesus Myth Theory''], for an overview of blogs by Bedard on the Jesus Myth Theory.}}

== Documentaries ==
Since 2005, several English-language documentaries have focused—at least in part—on the Christ myth theory:
* ''[[The God Who Wasn't There]]'' directed by [[Brian Flemming]] and featuring [[Richard Carrier]] and [[Robert M. Price]] (2005)
* ''[[The Pagan Christ#CBC documentary|The Pagan Christ]]'' produced by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] and featuring [[Tom Harpur]] (2007)
* ''[[Zeitgeist: The Movie]]'' directed by [[Peter Joseph]] (2007)
* ''The Hidden Story of Jesus'' produced by [[Channel 4]] and featuring [[Robert Beckford]] (2007)
* ''[[Religulous]]'' directed by [[Larry Charles]] and featuring [[Bill Maher]] (2008)
* ''[[Caesar's Messiah]]'' by Joseph Atwill (2013)

