{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}} {{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox sportsperson| | name = Gary Hooper | image = | imagesize = | caption = | fullname = Gary Leslie Hooper | nicknames = | nationality = {{AUS}} | club = | collegeteam = | birth_date =11 February 1939 | birth_place = [[Sydney]] | death_date = | death_place = | height = | weight = | medaltemplates= {{MedalSport | Athletics}} {{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}} {{MedalSilver|[[1960 Summer Paralympics|1960 Rome]]|Men's Precision Javelin B}} {{MedalGold | [[1964 Summer Paralympics|1964 Tokyo]] |Men's Wheelchair Dash above T10}} {{MedalSilver | [[1964 Summer Paralympics|1964 Tokyo]] |Men's Wheelchair Relay above T10}} {{MedalGold|[[1968 Summer Paralympics|1968 Tel Aviv]]|Men's 100&nbsp;m Wheelchair A}} {{MedalSilver|[[1968 Summer Paralympics|1968 Tel Aviv]]|Men's 4x40&nbsp;m Relay open}} {{MedalSilver|[[1968 Summer Paralympics|1968 Tel Aviv]]|Men's Shot Put B}} {{MedalSport | Weightlifting}} {{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}} {{MedalSilver | [[1964 Summer Paralympics|1964 Tokyo]] |Men's Lightweight }} }}
'''Gary Leslie Hooper''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]<ref name="mbe">{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1084398&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Hooper, Gary Leslie, MBE|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref> (born 11 February 1939) is an Australian Paralympic competitor. He won seven medals at three Paralympics from 1960 to 1968.
==Personal== Hooper was born on 11 February 1939 in Sydney.<ref name="oralhist">{{cite web|url=http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/4972103|title=Gary Hooper interviewed by Rob Willis|publisher=Australian Centre for Paralympic Studies oral history project|date=19 August 2010|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref> He never knew his biological father, and lived with his stepfather.<ref name="oralhist"/> He contracted [[poliomyelitis|polio]] at the age of eleven, and lost the use of both his legs.<ref name="oralhist"/>
He worked as a bookkeeper, and later as a public speaker and accessibility consultant.<ref name="oralhist"/> He was a judge in fencing at the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Olympics]].<ref name="oralhist"/> He has been married to Janice since 1964, and they have two sons.<ref name="oralhist"/>
==Career== At the [[1960 Summer Paralympics|1960 Rome Games]], Hooper won a silver medal in the Men's Precision Javelin B event.<ref name="IPC">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/search.php?sport=all&games=all&medal=all&npc=all&name=Hooper&fname=Gary&gender=all|title=Athlete Search Results|publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]]|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref> At the [[1964 Summer Paralympics|1964 Tokyo Games]], he won a gold medal in the Men's Wheelchair Dash above T10 event and two silver medals in the Men's Wheelchair Relay above T10 and Men's Lightweight weightlifting events;<ref name="IPC"/><ref name=Paralympic-results-520>{{cite book|page=520|title=Paralympic Games results : Rome 1960 to Atlanta 1996|author1=International Paralympic Committee|author2=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|location=Sydney, Australia|publisher=Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee|year=2000|oclc=223030936}}</ref> he also competed in swimming and wheelchair fencing at the games.<ref name="IPC"/> At the [[1968 Summer Paralympics|1968 Tel Aviv Games]], he won a gold medal in the Men's 100&nbsp;m Wheelchair A event and two silver medals in the Men's 4x40&nbsp;m Relay open and Men's Shot Put B events; he also competed in swimming, weightlifting, and wheelchair fencing at the games.<ref name="IPC"/> He participated in the [[1962 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games|1962]], [[1966 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games|1966]], and [[1970 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games|1970]] [[Commonwealth Paraplegic Games]] in [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], Jamaica, and [[Edinburgh]], respectively.<ref name="oralhist"/>
==Recognition== Hooper became a [[Order of the British Empire|Member of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1969 "for achievements at the Paraplegic Olympics".<ref name="mbe"/>
