'''Jim Wakeford''' (born 1944 in [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]], [[Saskatchewan]]) is a well-known [[medical marijuana]] advocate based in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. In 1989 Wakeford was diagnosed with the [[HIV virus]].<ref>Nate Hendley [http://www.cannabisculture.com/articles/1393.html "Jim Wakeford: Canada's best hope for medical marijuana?"] ''[[Cannabis Culture (magazine)|Cannabis Culture]]'' Nov 1, 1998.</ref> The medicines used to treat his illness made him nauseated and inhibited his appetite. Wakeford credits marijuana with helping treat the side effects of the medications used to keep him alive. Wakeford and his lawyer [[Alan Young (lawyer)|Alan Young]] challenged the [[Ontario Superior Court of Justice|Ontario Court's General Division]] for denying him, and other medical marijuana users, the right to use the drug. The [[Harvard University|Harvard]] paleontologist [[Stephen Jay Gould]] assisted Wakeford by testifying in the case, arguing that the illicit substance proved invaluable in treating the side effects of his cancer treatments. On September 7, 1998 Wakeford's suit against the government was dismissed. The judge ruled it was up to [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]] to overturn the law. In May 1999 the courts ruled that Wakeford could smoke and grow his own marijuana.<ref>Dana Larsen [http://www.cannabisculture.com/articles/1721.html "Canada's med-pot push"] ''[[Cannabis Culture (magazine)|Cannabis Culture]]'' Nov. 13, 2000</ref><ref>CBC. ''[http://archives.cbc.ca/IDCC-1-69-652-3598/life_society/marijuana/ The National]'' May 11, 1999.</ref>
