{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}} {{Infobox royalty|realm=mexico | title = Prince of Mexico | name = Salvador | full name = Salvador María de Iturbide y Huarte | image = | image_size = 250px | caption = | house = [[House of Iturbide|Iturbide]] | house-type=Imperial House | father =[[Agustín de Iturbide|Augustín I of Mexico]] | mother =[[Ana María de Huarte y Muñiz]] | birth_date =17 July 1820 | birth_place =[[Palace of Iturbide|Moncada Palace]] | death_date = 7 June 1856 (aged 35) | death_place =[[Tepic River]], [[Nayarit]] | place of burial= | religion =[[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]] | spouse = María del Rosario de Marzán y Guisasola |}}
'''Prince Salvador of Mexico''', also named '''Salvador de Iturbide y Huarte''' (17 July 1820 – 7 June 1856)<ref>[http://www.royalark.net/Mexico/mexico3.htm Royal Ark]</ref> was the eighth child (and third son) of [[Agustín de Iturbide|Agustín I of Mexico]] and [[Ana María de Huarte y Muñiz|Empress Ana Maria Huarte]]. He was married in 1845 to ''Doña'' María del Rosario de Marzán y Guisasola. His descendants, through his son [[Salvador de Iturbide y de Marzán]], are the current [[First Mexican Empire|pretenders to the Mexican Throne]].
==Biography== Prince Salvador was two years old when he was created ''Príncipe de México'' (Prince of Mexico) and styled [[Highness]] by the Mexican Congress. He had nine brothers and sisters; [[Agustín Jerónimo de Iturbide y Huarte| Prince Imperial Agustín Jerónimo]], [[Sabina de Iturbide y Huarte|Princess Sabina]], [[Sister Margarita of Jesus|Princess Juana]], Princess Josefa, Prince Ángel, Princess María, Princess Dolores, Prince Felipe, and Prince Agustín Cosme.
He was educated at [[Collège Sainte-Barbe]], Paris, [[Bourbon Restoration|France]], and in [[Vienna]], [[Austrian Empire|Austria]].
Salvador was the third in line to the throne, after his brother Ángel de Iturbide y Huarte. When [[Maximilian I of Mexico]] was crowned emperor, he contacted the [[House of Iturbide|Iturbide]] family to ask for the adoption of two boys: His Highness, [[Agustín de Iturbide y Green]], son of Ángel, and His Highness [[Salvador de Iturbide y Marzán]], son of Salvador.
He was drowned in a [[boating]] accident on the [[Tepic River]], [[Nayarit]], on 7 June 1856.
== Duties == * Secretary Mexican Legation in Washington, D.C. in 1849.
== Honours == ;National honours * Knight Grand Cross of the [[Mexican Imperial Orders|National Order of Our Lady of Guadalupe]] (13 August 1822).
